(Disclaimer: This deck requires you to have fair amount of APM, be warned! Try to get at least 10 materials attached to Plump or it might not be enough to win with C9 later on.)

Greetings! It's time unleash Catzilla and have a blast with C9 later on. If interested, keep reading!

 

Gameplan

1) Reach the board state as illustrated:

  • "Banisher of the Light" was Special Summoned by Saryuja. Also, Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon and have Ravenous with you. At one point, you will destroy Banisher, that's why...
    • Actually, you don't have to use Banisher. Instead, if you have, place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone. Since ME-PSY-YA costs UR to craft and I don't have two of those, I had to use Banisher as a substitute.

 

2) Then, Link Summon Reprodocus by using Panda + Saryuja as materials:

  • As you can see from these two pictures, you have to XYZ Summon Plump by using Nemeses + Formula as materials. Also, place him right behind Reprodocus, you will see why later on.

 

3) Since every card will be sent to Banish Zone (BZ) instead of GY, you can retrieve banished cards with "Primal Seed" duo. Fetch as many spells as you can, minimum 10 excluding combo pieces, with "Primal Seed" duo and then, destroy "Banisher" with Ravenous...

  • Or, ME-PSY-YA, but only if you have two of them and placed one of them to Pendulum Zone beforehand.

4) Then, play "Spell Reproduction" to discard two of your spells to GY and target "Spell Reproduction" to have it with you. This setup actually causes a loop. When you have discarded at least 10 spells except combo pieces, place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone. 

5) With ME-PSY-YA present, it's time to switch to "Primal Seed" setup. First, attach spells from GY to Plump. Then, use Book spells to reset its ability to do it again and retrieve Books with "Primal Seed" duo. After you have attached at least 10 spells, overlay into Happiness but don't forget to place behind Reprodocus:

 

6) Then, change the type of Happiness to "Machine" with Reprodocus. Now, you can lead the way to C9. Play "Astral Force" for Number 9 and "Barian's Force" for C9. Finally, trigger both abilities of C9 to explode your opponent:

  • If you want to watch the deck in action, click here!

deck_excerpt: C9 FTK ft. Mech Beast Lusterrex
deck_description:
Good day to you. In this deck, we will attach "Super Quantum" monsters to Lusterrex and lead the way with explosions of C9. Time to have a blast!

 

 

Gameplan

1) Place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon. While bringing forth Chaos Emperor, don't banish any Level 7 monsters by accident. Also, ME-PSY-YA and Chaos duo are needed for "Primal Seed" setup, where you can retrieve banished cards which can also include "White Layer" banished with "Seven Stars" for draw reasons...

  • Speaking of "Super Quantum" monsters, try using their abilities to draw a card and/or send "Super Quantum" monsters to GY to thin your deck.

2) Special Summon Ancient and Dark Strike with "Monster Reborn". Then, XYZ Summon Lusterrex by using both as materials...

  • Before you XYZ Summon Lusterrex, don't forget to use the ability of Dark Strike for burn damage. Best target would be Ravenous for 9 x 200 = 1800 damage.

3) Use the ability of Lusterrex to attach "Super Quantum" monsters from your hand or field. There are six of them, so attach every single one of them until Lusterrex has 8 materials in total...

  • To attach them from your field, "Monster Reborn" is your best friend.
  • To attach them from your hand, "Primal Seed" is your best friend.
  • To attach them again and again, Book spells are your best friends.

4) Play "Astral Force" to overlay into Number 9 and "Barian's Force" for Number C9. Now, you have 10 materials for C9.

5) Activate both abilities of C9 to deal 300 x 10 + 800 x 10 = 11000 damage in total for FTK. You should also deal at most 1800 damage with Dark Strike for good measure.

deck_excerpt: Bone Tower Mill Burn FTK ft. Dark Room of Nightmare + Paralyzing Chain
deck_description:
So, you might have heard of Bone Tower with its mill ability thanks to Mayakashi. What if I told you there is no need for that? Rather than Mayakashi archetype, you can simply use a Turbo Booster alongside burn cards. Yes, you heard me right. If you don't believe me, why don't you have a look at the guide?

 

 

Gameplan

1) At one point, play "Double Summon". Also, don't forget to activate the ability of "Abyss Dweller" to block the activation of anything within your opponent's GY. It's crucial to be not disturbed.

2) Special Summon Bone Tower with Saryuja, right behind its Extra Monster Zone. Then, Normal Summon Meiru. Afterwards, Link Summon Reprodocus, right above Bone Tower.

3) Activate Reprodocus and change the attribute of Bone Tower to anything other than LIGHT and DARK. Reason is that we don't want Bone Tower being negated by Meiru.

4) Activate "Zombie World" alongside "Dark Room of Nightmare" + "Paralyzing Chain". Then, Special Summon Turbo Booster. Since everything on the field and in the GYs become Zombie, you can mill your opponent with any kind of Special Summon, in addition to burning your opponent to death with Nightmare and Chain.

5) What makes it endless is returning Booster to your hand with Birdman. Although Meiru negates the effects of LIGHT and DARK monsters, it doesn't negate their costs. So, Birdman can return Booster to your hand (cost) and Birdman can stay in your hand instead of Special Summoning to the field (effect) thanks to negate of Meiru, since Birdman is a DARK monster...

  • Simply put, Birdman and Booster can use their effects forever. Special Summon Booster and return to hand with Birdman, while Bone Tower and Nightmare + Chain kills your opponent.

Hey there! It has been a while since I have experimented with Lantron, where I could reflect incoming damage from the opponent right back at them. This time it will be with Number 35. Let me explain how.

 

 

Gameplan

1) Place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon. This setup is needed to find banished cards with "Primal Seed" duo, which will be combo pieces later on.

2) Have four monsters present with "Monster Reborn" and "Treasure Panda". Then, replace one of Exodia pieces with Incarnate.

3) Target "Galaxy Queen's Light" on Incarnate to adjust the level of your monsters to 10. Then, excluding Chaos, XYZ Summon 2 x Number 35 by using 4 monsters as materials.

4) Either Special Summon Lantron with Saryuja or via "Monster Reborn", if you have sent Lantron to GY with Dugares/Ravenous.

5) Give your opponent 2 x Number 35 monsters with "Shien's Spy".

6) Revive any monster with "Monster Reborn". What is going to happen is that 2 x Number 35 monsters will deal 2 x 600 = 1200 damage in total because you have Special Summoned a monster. However, Lantron will reflect said damage to your opponent.

7) Revive a monster with "Monster Reborn" and destroy it with "Offerings to the Doomed". Rinse and repeat until your opponent is dead.

The goal of this deck was to build something fun to play that can put the original fusions from the GX era to some use. The main play of the deck is using Elemental HERO Stratos to search for Elemental HERO Neos. Then the goal becomes to fuse them into the new Elemental HERO Flame Wingman - Infernal Rage which in turn gets you either Favorite Contact to turn the Elemental HERO Neos in your grave and the Elemental HERO Flame Wingman - Infernal Rage you just summoned into either Wake Up Your Elemental HERO in an attempt to burn for game, or Elemental HERO Shining Neos Wingman  to destroy any pesky backrow or problematic monster cards in the rare case that they can be destroyed. Alternatively you can search for Favorite Hero providing your somewhat dated hero fusions with targetting protection and in some cases, a strong attack boost.

Elemental HERO Flame Wingman - Infernal Rage can tribute himself to summon an elemental hero monster from the deck or extra deck that is level 7 or lower and cannot be normal summoned or set. This gives you access to most of the original heroes from back in the day as well as all of the single neo-spacian contact fusions. With your searched Favorite Hero , these monsters can become somewhat formidable as at the beginning of the . At the start of the battle phase you can activate a field spell from the deck which means your equiped monster gains attack equal to its defence and becomes immune to tagetting. If you open with A Hero Lives you can pay 4000LP to search your statos starter which is a 4000 attack boost for Elemental HERO Air Neos he'd gain a further 2500 from Favorite Hero due to having 2000 defence and 500 from searching Neo Space and an Elemental HERO Honest Neos can boost him further to frankly insane numbers for otk potential.

deck_excerpt: Take Yugioh's "boss rush" archetype to the next level with Triple Tactics Thrust on Masterduel Ladder!
deck_description:
Generaider has been one of the coolest archetypes to ever come out in my opinion. As a RPG connoisseur, the idea of piloting a deck as the dungeon master pitting your opponent through a "boss rush" scenario is so cool! It's been a couple months since I've updated this deck, so I decided to create a guide/decklist that would best fit the current metagame.

With the release of the "Flames of Fury" pack in Masterduel, Generaider receives three copies of Triple Tactics Thrust - an incredible card allowing the deck another way to get Boss Stage on the field and increased capability to play going second (an ability it sorely lacks)! 

This deck can notably play under Dimension Shifter/Ariseheart's banish floodgates as well! 

Even more consistent and strong with the recent new support and with TTThrust, pure Generaider is now able to stuff a whopping 20+ staples in their decklist, allowing it to compete with Masterduel's merciless meta. 

Be your opponent's final BOSS as you pilot Generaider!

ARCHETYPES AND DECKBUILDING

 
No other engines mean that Generaider has more room for staple cards to specifically counter the meta - the Maxx "C" package and  the newly introduced TTThrust and it's associated cards - what I like to call the "TTThrust package." 
 
Since Generaider is incentivized to include more level 9s with the addition of Vala and Laevateinn, ten level 9 Generaider bosses are used to enable the deck go into rank 9 XYZ plays. Laevatein is your main go-to rank 9, however, some situations may call for Infinitrack Earth Slicer or Enterblathnir. Some hands allow for four level 9 Generaider to be deployed on the board, so you can hand-rip two cards from your opponent's hand (Double Enterblathnir) then make Utopic Draco Future! Combos will be explained below.
 
3 Hop Ear Squadron is particularly effective in this deck. During your opponent's turn, you can synchro two tokens away with Hop Ear Squadron to hand rip your opponent for one card and make Baronne De Fleur!
 
3 Triple Tactics Thrust is used because of it's immense versatility. It's targets for searching from deck are Triple Tactics Talent, Evenly Matched and Appointer of the Red Lotus. If needed, Thrust can also set Generaider Boss Fight to get your engine started. Always live because of the nearly 90% usage of Ash/Maxx "C," you can always search out for your starter to set from deck, Generaider Boss Fight or search a board breaker to punish your opponent. 
 
There are 9 ways to search Generaider Boss Stage in this deck + the 3 Boss Stages themselves - giving you a total of 12 ways to get your all-important field spell on board. TTThrust also indirect searches Boss Stage by setting Boss Fight from deck. 
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
Generaiders function as a control strategy, negating and interrupting your opponent until your giant beatsticks can attack for game. Pure Generaider combos are simple since the strategy is so straightforward. Do not underestimate it's simplicity, since it is very potent!
 
Here are the combos for Generaider:
 
Vala, Seidhr of the Generaider Bosses + Mardel, Generaider Boss of Light = Boss Stage and Laevatein
  1. Activate Vala's effect to summon herself by sending Mardel to the GY. 
  2. On summon, activate Vala's on-field effect to summon a Mardel from your GY/hand.
  3. Mardel searches Boss Stage. If you have another Generaider on hand, search Boss Quest instead, then search Boss Stage + Another Generaider S/T. 
  4. Activate Boss Stage.
  5. XYZ summon Laevatein using Vala + Mardel. 
Vala, Seidhr of the Generaider Bosses + Any level 9 Generaider + World Legacy Monstrosity = Boss Stage, 2 card hand-rip and Utopic Draco Future
  1. Activate Vala's effect to summon herself by sending level 9 Generaider to the GY. 
  2. On summon, activate Vala's on-field effect to summon a level 9 Generaider from your GY/hand.
  3. Activate Monstrosity targeting Vala on the field. Summon from deck Mardel and another level 9 Generaider. 
  4. Mardel searches Boss Stage. If you have another Generaider on hand, search Boss Quest instead, then search Boss Stage + Another Generaider S/T. 
  5. Activate Boss Stage.
  6. XYZ summon Enterblathnir. Activate it's effect to banish a random card from your opponent's hand. 
  7. Repeat step 6. Banish a second card from your opponent's hand. 
  8. XYZ summon Utopic Future by overlaying your two Enterblathnirs.
  9. XYZ summon Utopic Draco Future using your Utopic Future. 

Hop Ear Squadron + 2 Generaider Tokens = 1 card hand-rip and Baronne De Fleur

  1. During your opponent's draw phase, summon Harr, Generaider Boss of Storms from deck. 
  2. During your opponent's main phase, negate your opponent's card effect with Harr, using two tokens so Hop Ear can use their effect. 
  3. Synchro summon using Hop Ear Squadron from hand + Generaider token for Desert Locusts. 
  4. On summon, discard a card from your opponent's hand with Desert Locusts. 
  5. Synchro summon using Desert Locusts + Generaider Token for Baronne De Fleur. 
Going first, it is imperative that the Duelist always establish Generaider Boss Stage. Everything else is just extra in comparison. Almost every hand would end on Laevatein's "XYZ Superpoly" and Boss Stage's summon from deck of another Generaider Boss. However, the most incredible hands can end on Enterblathnir's double hand-rip, Utopic Draco Future's monster negate/steal, Desert Locust's hand-rip and Baronne De Fleur. Also, this deck boasts 15+ staple slots, so you hand can have an Ash Blossom, Impermanence, etc. in hand for further interruption. 
 
Going second, this deck's ample space enables it to side in a multitude of going second cards. After an enemy's board has been sufficiently weakened, you can summon beefy beatsticks to beat down your opponent's monsters in the battle phase, then in main phase 2 you can use Laevatein to XYZ superpoly away their surviving monsters, backrow, and GY.

GENERAL TIPS 

  • Although somewhat limiting, this deck can still play relatively comfortably under Dimension Shifter, Dimensional Fissure and Macro Cosmos. With Ariseheart and Dimension Shifter so common on ladder right now, Generaider is one of the few decks that can still compete under those floodgates. 
  • A huge weakness this deck has is Cosmic Cyclone/Runick Destruction/Twin Twister on your Boss Stage. That usually ends most of your interaction and interruption vs. your opponent. Thankfully, these cards are relatively rare in the current iteration of Masterduel meta. 
  • Summon Loptr with Generaider Boss Stage first to give all your Generaider monsters and tokens an attack boost. Opponents tend to attack the low ATK tokens since they're a weak point in your defense. Tribute them before they get a chance to! 
  • If one of your Generaider monsters get negated or rendered useless, you can tribute it with Loptr to summon another Generaider Boss from deck, giving you another form of interaction. Also, if your opponent targets your Generaider monster with a card effect, you can quick effect tribute them with Loptr so they can dodge the effect!

CONCLUDING REMARKS

Triple Tactics Thrust changes the very deck builds of Masterduel ladder, including Generaider. With these cards, Generaider can now confidently go second while also having more access to it's engine! It's an incredible card that boosts the power of Generaider!


All in all, this older deck is granted new life for today's meta with their two very strong support cards Laevateinn and Vala. Triple Tactics Thrust from the Flames of Fury pack give the deck extra playability as well, allowing it to contest confidently meta decks on ladder. 

 

 GLHF Duelists!
banish

deck_excerpt: Diabellestarr Rescue-ACE  / China City Tour 2023-Wuhan Station Top 4
deck_description:
Category: Tournament Meta Deck OCG

 

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

 

Creator:  秦始皇

 

Tournament: China City Tour 2023-Wuhan Station

Placement: Top 4

(Disclaimer: This deck requires you to have fair amount of APM, be warned! Try to get at least 10 materials attached to Number 38 or it might not be enough to win with C9 later on.)

Greetings! Time to bring Harbinger of Galaxies, Number 38. Number 38 is ready to launch a nuclear satellite called Number C9. Just be careful out there!

 

 

Gameplan

1) Place ME-PSY-YA and Xiangsheng on Pendulum Zones. Then, Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon...

  • ME-PSY-YA and Chaos Emperor are needed for "Primal Seed" interactions, where we will find combo pieces from Banish Zone (BZ).
  • Xiangsheng is here for adjusting Rank of Number 38 from 8 to 7, so that we can lead the way with Number 9 later on.

2) When Chaos Emperor is here, revive 2 x Level monsters with "Monster Reborn". Then, target Chaos Emperor with "Galaxy Queen's Light" to set these two to 8.

3) XYZ Summon Number 38 by using them as materials. Don't use anything else, including Chaos Emperor.

4) To attach materials into Number 38, you need to negate your spells. If you have changed "Activation Confirmation" within "Duel" from settings into "Switch + Hold", you can hold down the left mouse button after you have played a spell. Changing from "OFF" to "ON", game will ask you if you want to negate the spell, so that you can attach it to Number 38. Just don't negate combo pieces and attach them by accident, then you will be fine.

5) To repeat what was explained in #4, you need to flip up and down Number 38 with Book spells because the attachment ability of Number 38 isn't hard once per turn. While doing so, don't forget to find Book spells with "Primal Seed" setup explained in #1.

6) When you have attached enough materials to Number 38, which should be at least 10, revive Ancient with "Monster Reborn". Then, activate Xiangsheng and target Number 38 alongside Ancient to change the Rank of Number 38 from 8 to 7. Next is activating "Clockwork Night" to change the Type of Number 38 into "Machine".

7) With Rank and Type modifications done, you can activate "Astral Force" to overlay into Number 9. Then, you can lead the way with "Barian's Force" to Number C9.

8) Activate both abilities of C9 to deal huge damage and win the game.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Monster Reborn" is given for free, if you have played the tutorial to save 30 UR!

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Into The Void" + "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Primal Seed" + "Pot of Acquistiveness" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 30 SR and 60 UR!

- "Number 60: Dugares the Timeless" + "Rank-Up-Magic Astral Force" can be found within "Number Recall" Secret Pack to save 60 SR!

- "Rank-Up-Magic Barian's Force" can be found within "Sword of the Seventh One" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Number 9: Dyson Sphere" can be found within "Colossal Mech" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Formula Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Number 38" can be found within "Nebula Cyclone" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 570 SR and 150 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. If you have any questions, feel free to ask. Have fun in Master Duel!

Gameplan

1) Place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon. This is needed to find combo pieces from Banish Zone (BZ) with "Primal Seed" cards.

2) Special Summon Sharnga >>> Vata >>> Caligo, in explained order. Clear some of Main Monster Zones (MMZ) and Extra Monster Zone (EMZ) with "Offerings to the Doomed" for space. Then, XYZ Summon Number 43 with these three and place it on EMZ...

Just me messing around with Ananta. I think it's a card that hasn't been cracked yet, be it because of the underwhelming power of Reptiles in Edison or because it's a very janky card in of itself that does need work to see effective results. Feel like this build is a bit more flexiable than just committing fully to one specific strat, which is why there's a bit of a mix in the side in terms of what exactly the deck wants to do and not do, so you got a bit of Alien, you run the regular Reptilianne engine to skim the deck, etc etc. Ananta regardless is a key monster for purely building up pressure and being consistent reliable field removal.

You think playing 3x Ananta would brick starting hands; I thought so as well; but for the vast majority of test showings I've had no such issue at all. It's a bit of a issue at points when you draw one out of the blue if you're not correctly set up, otherwise they seem pretty well balanced with the rest of the deck.

Quick card by card:

Diviner of the Herald : Can be used for the common purpose of sending Herald of the Arc Light or Elder Entity N'tss for effect, but can also use its secondary effect (did you even realize it had one??) to summon Novox, the Silenforcer Disciple from deck or hand when tributed.

Novox, the Silenforcer Disciple : Searches Silenforcing Barrier (which can search again) or Silenforcing Authority and can be used as full tribute summon cost.

Sauravis, the Sagely Silenforcer Dragon : Basically a free body and free ritual monster summon

Saffira, the Wise Silenforcer Queen :Just... Yes. Searcher, check. Put ritual spell in grave to summon Sauravis, the Sagely Silenforcer Dragon or to grab later, check. Acts as a ritual spell in grave, check.

Libromancer engine in short: They search each other when you have a ritual in hand and let you summon Libromancer Doombroker 

Sauravis, the Ancient and Ascended : In hand targeting protection and on field summon negation effect? Yes please.

Skull Guardian, the Silenforcing Protector : Omni negate and destroy, search deck, and beat stick.

Cyber Angel Benten : Searches when tributed.

Libromancer Doombroker : Searches Libromancer Intervention , direct attack, and removal. Can be summon through libromancer engine.

Extra deck is interchangeable other than Herald of the Arc Light and at least one Elder Entity N'tss

Hi! In this deck, we will win with Number 43 alongside Lead Yoke. By detaching materials from Lead Yoke, you can find the lethal range. Let me explain.

 

 

Gameplan

1) Place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon to find combo pieces with "Primal Seed" cards.

2) Special Summon Sharnga >>> Harmattan >>> Caligo, in explained order. With the trio alongside "Monster Reborn" + "Offerings to the Doomed" duo, XYZ Summon 2 x Number 43 first and then, 1 x Javelin.

3) Change the attribute of Javelin to FIRE with Scroll. Then, play Astral Force to bring forth Lead Yoke.

4) When you try to destroy Lead Yoke with Offerings, you can increase its ATK by 800 at the cost of detaching one material. To make a loop, add "Overlay Regen" into equation and you can raise the ATK of Lead Yoke as much as you want.

5) When you think you had it enough, play "Mystik Wok" and target on Lead Yoke. Choose its ATK to convert big chunk of healing into damage with 2 x Number 43 monsters for fatality.

This is the Odd-Eyes decklist that got me into Master Rank.I'm a Odd-Eyes/Pendulum main who plays Odd-Eyes Pals for more than 2 years and it's my favourite deck and summoning type,so I'm gonna share some tips and thoughts about the deck. :D

1-Usually 2 butler + foolish burial is the best,but because we're in a Kashtira format now in MD,foolish burial is a really bad spell to have
2-Book/TTT/Fenrir is our only way to win over Arise,and although I would love too run more copies of TTT/Thrust + Herald and other staples,the deck don't have the space to do it so because of the existence of Maxx C,making 3 Ash + 2 called by + 3 Maxx C a core,and any more card removed for more staples the deck bricks really bad
3-I'm a sucker for absolute and meteorburst,so I'm running then.Tbh the cards are really underrated,and they bring a ton of versatility to the deck,making Rebellion Overlord waaaay more consistent.If turn 1 just prosp them
4-If you get Maxx C'ed,try to make Bagooska if possible and pray,he's the cause of our misery
5-A good end board looks like: 3-4 Mat Apo,Vortex,Baronne and Chaos Angel
6-Chaos Angel feels really good to have because Kash can't deal with him with a Light and Dark materials,wich the deck can make really easily,and a battle protection for Apo
7-Accesscode and Rebellion are our chad boardbreakers.Usually you have 3/4 pop of Access + 3 Atk with Rebellion,it's insane
8-Darkwurm SUCKS for the deck.It makes sense on paper but It's toooo bricky and don't synergizes with the Odd-Eyes and Performapal engines,plus having to add Dragon Shrine to use him consistantly feels like a waste of space
9-Sky Iris feels nice at 1.Cards like duelist alliance and Spiral Flame Strike aren't bad but Sky Iris is waaay better than all of them because it give us access to anything that we might need + procs Astrograph and Gentrude

For combos,diverse decklists,events and such,you can catch me on my youtube channel https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCMRrS9vJJ9M8ZfzNrd7Lwkw

After playing this deck in a simulator for two months and finally getting the chance to play it in an actual paper format with the Age of Overlord Premiere! event, I'm finally feeling confident enough to say this: the support pushes this deck to being much better than either I or anyone else has been giving it credit for. I'm going to try to give these cards a legitimate write-up, in the hopes that I can get players to give it a try.

I'll start with an explanation on the ratios of the Nouvelles and their adjacent support in the deck, to help you understand why you're running it like this.

  • Foie Glasya and Confiras are both at 1 since neither of them actually do anything to start your combos and are purely extenders - Foie Glasya is a valid target for Poeltis's summon if you don't need a second Balameuniere while simultaneously acting as GY interruption if brought out during your opponent's plays, while Confiras is mainly there if all of your Poeltis are tied up, or you specifically need a backrow pop or to force your opponent's cards into attack. Even if that's not really much, Confiras and Meat Recipe can be simultaneously added with Pre-Preparation of Rites, since Meat Recipe specifically lists Confiras in its effect, so it can be grabbed in an emergency.
  • Every other Nouvelles Ritual Monster is at 2 - Nouvelles has some pretty solid search power, so running less than 3 of each Ritual Monster works, in addition to reducing the brickiness that Ritual Decks often have.
  • Poissoniere at 3, as well as Culinary Confrontation - you almost always want to see these, as Poissoniere searches either Buerillabaise or a Recipe, and Culinary Confrontation is an E-Tele for Poissoniere.
  • Fish Recipe is at 3, while Meat Recipe is at 1 - Fish Recipe is just better to start your Ritual Plays, since it's searchable with Pre-Prep and itself can search Meat Recipe.
  • Today's Menu at 3 - it's a free search. Even if it does give your opponent some agency in what you add, you're still going to go +1 by using it (or Neutral if your opponent gives you Poissoniere - which, as mentioned before, is still good).
  • Nouvelles Restaurant can be run at 1, but I prefer it at 2. It'll be on your first turn endboard quite often whether or not you draw it, but having a second copy does create a small resource loop that can constantly shuffle the first back into your deck to repeatedly grab Chef's Special Recipe after it's been spent.
  • Chef's Special Recipe is run at 1 - you don't want to start with it, but like Restaurant, you can often end with it. It's also able to be grabbed from the GY by activating another Restaurant as part of that resource loop, meaning you never really need a second.
  • Hungry Burger is at 1 - it purely exists to be a valid target for Baelgrill's Quick Effect. It's the brickiest brick in your deck, but is still required for that one last removal.

As for the non-engine cards, it should be fairly obvious why you run those ratios. Pre-Preparation of Rites and Diviner of the Herald are at 3 because they search engine pieces, start combos, or do both. The Impcantations are run at 2 of each, which creates a balance of both being able to see them consistently while also not crowding your deck with them. And Ash Blossom and Imperm are both at 3 because hand trap great.

The Extra Deck is a combination of Ritual Fodder and Game-Closers, with a couple of things in-between. 

  • Patissciel Couverture is run because it turns Culinary Confrontation online - you're giving it to your opponent to serve as fodder for your plays. 
  • Herald of the Arc Light and Elder Entity N'Tss are both pitch fodder for Diviner of the Herald; Arc Light helps you set up by searching for a Ritual piece, while N'Tss can remove a piece of the opponent's board in a pinch. 
  • Nephthys, the Sacred Flame is your primary game-closer - if you're doing the math and need just a bit more damage to clear an opponent's board, you can sack three of your lower-power Ritual Monsters to bring out a 4800 ATK, indestructible, untargetable beater to finish things off. 
  • Dyna Mondo is a panic option if you're running out of plays and need to get rid of something. It also lets you bring back a Nouvelles from the Graveyard on your opponent's turn, which does let you do some interesting plays while getting a Nouvelles floodgate back on the field.
  • Relinquished Anima can be summoned with Poissoniere or Buerillabaise and just punishes an opponent for careless zone placement - non-destruction removal is always nice, even if this deck already has no shortage of it.
  • Knightmare Unicorn has its bounce, but is mostly there for a Link Climb into Accesscode Talker, for if you still need something a bit more powerful than even Nephthys can provide.
  • Chaos Angel and Baronne de Fleur are generic Synchro bosses that won't come out often, but are able to be brought out with a small amount of set-up. Your Nouvelles can mostly do the job, but if you need a little push in power, they are an option. 
  • Super Starslayer TY-PHON - Sky Crisis is a floodgate on legs that can block anything above 3000 ATK - which all of your main deck monsters slip under easily. If your opponent brings out some high-level Extra Deck monsters, you can get something out, go into this, and block them for a turn.

Finally, the Side Deck is packed with your generic counterpick tools.

  • Nibiru is run for the blow-out against summon-heavy decks. I prefer running it over Evenly Matched since it gives your opponent a Token that you can use for your own Nouvelles plays.
  • Dark Ruler No More helps you overcome stacked negate boards, which is very useful going second, especially since you need plenty of effects to get this deck going.
  • Kaijus help get rid of your opponent's immune bosses, like Expurrely Noir. You could alternatively run Herald of the Abyss, but I prefer the Kaiju to, once again, get a useless body on your opponent's field for your own plays.
  • Lightning Storm and Harpie's Feather Duster just help clear out the backrow - removing potential floodgates really helps to keep this deck online.
  • Gozen Match's uses are two-fold. Its basic play is just a good floodgate that stops some decks like Floo and Kashtira, while your mostly-DARK Monsters can play under it. However, you can perform a lock if you draw it along with Culinary Confrontation, which puts a monster on your opponent's board - if your opponent doesn't run DARK monsters or backrow removal, they're out of luck.

The most common pieces on an end-board you'll be going for are a Balameuniere summoned with a Nouvelles effect and a set Chef's Special Recipe. Anything else you can get on the field is gravy, especially if you can summon Poeltis or Foie Glasya on your turn 1 and keep it on your field, but these cards by themselves are capable of forcing your opponent to second-guess quite a lot of their plays, especially when their Normal Summon is involved.

I'll start with a basic combo line. Your hand will start with Poissoniere de Nouvelles, Poeltis or Foie Glasya de Nouvelles (either works), Fish Recipe or Buerillabaise de Nouvelles (either works), and one Monster of level 3 or higher. This seems a bit complex and specific at first, but this deck is running plenty of search power and generic cards that can turn into these cards (Pre-Preparation of Rites gets you both Fish Recipe and Buerillabaise, Today's Menu can snag either Foie Glasya or Poeltis, etc.) - with a bit of experience, you'll be able to grab what you need or extend even further.

  1. Normal Summon Poissoniere de Nouvelles
    • On Summon: Activate Poissoniere
    • Resolve: Add Fish Recipe/Buerillabaise (Whatever you're missing)
  2. Activate Fish Recipe
    • Resolve: Tribute Poissoniere, Ritual Summon Buerillabaise de Nouvelles, add Meat Recipe
    • On Resolution: Buerillabaise CL1, Poissoniere CL2
      • Resolve: Scale Poissoniere, Excavate and add (if anything is hit)
  3. Activate Meat Recipe
    • Resolve: Tribute Level 3+ in hand, Ritual Summon Poeltis/Foie Glasya de Nouvelles
    • On Resolution: Activate Poeltis/Foie Glasya
      • Resolve: Whatever effect was activated (NOTE: If you summoned Foie Glasya to field, keep at least one Recipe in your own GY)
  4. Use Poissoniere target Buerillabaise CL1, Trigger Poeltis/Foie Glasya CL2
    • Resolve: Tribute Buerillabaise + Poeltis/Foie Glasya to Summon Balameuniere de Nouvelles, Special Summon Poissoniere from scale
    • On Resolution: Activate Balameuniere
      • Resolve: Add Nouvelles Restaurant ~ At Table
  5. Activate Nouvelles Restaurant
    • Resolve: Add Chef's Special Recipe
  6. Set Chef's Special Recipe
  7. If you have a valid target in hand, use Nouvelles Restaurant to mulligan for a hand-trap
  8. On End Phase: Use Nouvelles Restaurant, target one Recipe + one other GY target
    • Resolve: Return to deck, draw 1

With this board, your Balameuniere (which was summoned using a Nouvelles Monster's effect) can snipe your opponent's Normal Summon (or any Attack Position monster they bring out, if they choose not to summon in Defense) to bring out Baelgrill de Nouvelles on your opponent's turn. When done this way, Baelgrill will DRNM your opponent's Monsters and any face-up Spells/Traps they might have, as well as completely board-wiping their monsters, regardless of whether or not they're in Defense Position. Chef's Special can omni-negate something if the opponent would have Evenly Matched or Dark Ruler No More to try to stop Balameuniere as well, and when Baelgrill is on field, you get one more Quick Effect Tribute to remove one more thing your opponent might try to bring out.

This is also an incredibly basic opening board - Nouvelles is pretty interesting in that, while its pure-engine plays can get you going, a few non-engine pieces can not only extend you even further, but can sometimes do it with less resources burned. If your starting hand contains either Diviner of the Herald, an Impcantation, or Culinary Confrontation, you're able to extend much farther and get a more complex Nouvelles setup. To be more specific with each, Diviner, if Tributed (which all of your Ritual Summons do) will be able to Special Summon Poissoniere from your Deck for the extra search power and extension. The Impcantations grab a missing piece for your Ritual plays while simultaneously getting more bodies on the field for both Ritual Summons and Nouvelles Summons. And Culinary Confrontation is one of the most versatile Spells for the Nouvelles archetype - it can be used both for preparation, as it E-Teles Poissoniere while getting a second body on the field for your Nouvelles Summons, and it can be used to break walls, as you can use it on your opponent's turn if they're summoning in Defense to get an Attack Position body on the field for Balameuniere to use to bring out Baelgrill and break the opponent's field.

Such a fun deck. It's obviously not perfect, but it has a winning matchup against decks like Floowandereeze (who have trouble getting monsters in Defense) and various Link Climb decks. It's easy to pick up and learn, but has enough of a ceiling where there may be plenty of good plays in any situation. I've even been able to land match wins against Swordsoul-Tenyi and Purrely with this exact profile. It's a deceptively difficult deck for opponents to work around that specializes in non-destruction removal of anything and everything that can be thrown at it, and even though it revolves around the funny Hungry Burger, you'll be hard-pressed to call it a meme when you're cooking up opponents left and right.

I thought it would be a good idea to make 3 Decks for each major character in the series.

These Decks could be switched around when battled in a game, instead of always the same one (it adds variety, unpredictability and difficulty this way). I kept 1 copy of banned cards only, but still decided to use them (even though some of them might be considerd cheap). Mostly the games have different Decks for each character (Tag Force), but they scale up in difficulty instead of all of them being tough to beat (it's a good practice, but more advanced players will find this more interesting, I believe). 

In a possible future, I might consider adding a Side Deck to each of them.

---

The DM Era Decks follow the Goat Format's Banlist, but they may also have a few extra cards (namely, cards that were released afterwards but still appeared on the first anime).

This is Yugi's "Silent Swordsman" Deck. To help the deck perform well, it has a little Warrior engine in it.

I've also added 2 Banned cards to it, "Monster Reborn" and "Dark Hole" (since they're very iconic Yugi cards) and "Gold Sarcophagus", that, while it was released after Goat Format, it is a card that is also extremely iconic of Yugi's. Nonetheless, the side Deck has nice substitutes to make it legal fro Goat Format (crazy that those cards are considered way better nowadays than the banned ones).

Combination of Cyber Dragon & Blue-eyes White Dragon

Greetings! In this deck, we will start with Number 79 and lead the way with C9 for big explosion. Here is how.

 

 

Gameplan

1) XYZ Summon Number 79 by using 2 x Cthugua as materials, right behind at one of Extra Monster Zones (EMZ).

2) Place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon to find combo pieces from Banish Zone (BZ) with "Primal Seed" cards.

3) Flip Number 79 up and down with Book spells to attach all "Battlin' Boxer" monsters, either from your hand or GY. Don't forget to find Book spells with "Primal Seed" cards to repeat the process.

4) Link Summon Reprodocus right above Number 79 and play "Barian's Force" to bring forth C39. Then, change the type of C39 to "Machine" via Reprodocus.

5) Next up is to play "Astral Force" twice to lead the way with "Lusterrex" and "Number 9". If you don't have Lusterrex, swap it with "Number C6", seen in "Side Deck".

6) Finally, play "Barian's Force" one more time to summon C9. Activate both abilities for the FTK.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Reinforcement of the Army" is given for free, if you have played the tutorial to save 30 UR!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 600 SR and 90 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

deck_excerpt: Curse Reflection Doll FTK ft. Resurgent
deck_description:
Heya! It looks like I found how to FTK without Linewalker. Let me explain real quick.

 

 

Gameplan

1) Let "Black Garden" plant at least one rose to opposing side and destroy Garden with Ancient/Ravenous. Destroying Garden is crucial because we don't want any ATK adjustment coming from Garden. Then, replace the rose with Jizukiru.

2) Equip Jizukiru with United We Stand + Mage Power + Psychic Blade to boost its ATK by big margin...

  • If you have, equip Jizukiru with 3 x United We Stand instead of one and remove Psychic Blade. Since United We Stand costs UR to craft and I got one for free, I had to use Mage Power as substitute.
  • Be mindful that United We Stand increases ATK with respect to monsters you have. It doesn't count with respect to your opponent's.
  • If you are curious of hypothetical setup for maximum damage, here is the math:
    • 3 x United We Stand >>> 3 x (800 x 6) = 14400 damage
    • 1 x Mage Power >>> 500 x 5 = 2500 damage
    • Jizukiru >>> 3300 damage
    • Saryuja >>> 300 damage (optional)
    • Total = 14400 + 2500 + 3300 + 300 = 20500 damage.

3) Special Summon Pineapple with Saryuja. This is a must because we don't have any Plant monsters but Pineapple + Resurgent and Resurgent needs at most four Plant monsters to Link Summon. Thank goodness Pineapple can change the type of monsters you control to Plant.

4) Link Summon Resurgent and target Jizukiru, when you have "Curse Reflection Doll" in your hand. Then, chain into Doll to deal 13000 damage for the FTK...

  • Even if your budget can't afford to craft "United We Stand", you can still FTK your opponent with 3 x Mage Power + 1 x Psychic Blade. When chained into Doll, here is the math for total damage:
    • 3 x Mage Power >>> 3 x (500 x 5) = 7500 damage
    • 1 x Psychic Blade >>> 2000 damage
    • Jizukiru >>> 3300 damage
    • Saryuja >>> 300 damage (optional)
    • Total = 7500 + 2000 + 3300 + 300 = 13100 damage.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Into The Void" + "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Pot of Acquistiveness" + "Ravenous" + "United We Stand" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 60 SR and 30 UR!

- "Black Garden" can be found within "Exquisite Jet-Black Rose" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Benghalancer the Resurgent" can be found within "Seedling Soul Fey" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Daigusto Emeral" can be found within "Ties to Mother Nature" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Formula Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 60 SR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 570 SR and 90 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. If you have any questions, feel free to ask. Have fun in Master Duel!

deck_excerpt: C9 FTK ft. Lyrilusc - Bird Sanctuary
deck_description:
Uh oh! It looks like angry birds are ready for aerial strike. Beware of Lyrilusc and their satellite C9!

 

 

Gameplan

1) XYZ Summon your first Lyrilusc, by using 3 x Sapphire as material. If you have sent 3 x Warbler to GY with Dugares/Ravenous, you can attach them with Sapphire...

  • If possible, before you XYZ Summon, activate "Kahyoreigetsu" to return Saryuja to Extra Deck. Therefore, you can XYZ Summon Lyrilusc to Extra Monster Zone (EMZ), where you can spare Main Monster Zone (MMZ) for Level 1 dudes later on.

2) XYZ Summon your second Lyrilusc, by using as much Level 1 dudes as possible...

  • If they are in your deck, Panda is your best friend.
  • If they are in your hand, Pendulum Summon is your best friend.
  • You can bring forth at most 4 x Level 1 monsters, no matter how you can setup your board, just saying.

3) Merge these two with "Lyrilusc - Bird Sanctuary". Then, revive "Stardust Charge Warrior" with "Monster Reborn".

4) Place and activate Xiangsheng to change the Rank of your Lyrilusc to 6 by targeting Stardust.

5) Next, play this combo in order: Argent Chaos Force >>> Number C6 >>> Astral Force >>> Number 9 >>> Argent Chaos Force >>> Number C9

6) Activate both abilities of C9 for deadly aerial satellite launch to kill your opponent.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Monster Reborn" is given for free, if you have played the tutorial to save 30 UR!

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Into The Void" + "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Pot of Acquistiveness" + "Ravenous" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 60 SR!

- "Number 60: Dugares the Timeless" + "Rank-Up-Magic Astral Force" can be found within "Number Recall" Secret Pack to save 60 SR!

- "Number C6" can be found within "Timeworn Legacies" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Rank-Up-Magic Argent Chaos Force" can be found either within "Timeworn Legacies" or  "Colossal Mech" to save 30 UR!

- "Number 9: Dyson Sphere" can be found within "Colossal Mech" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Formula Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Lyrilusc - Assembled Nightingale" and "Lyrilusc - Promenade Thrush" can be found within "Moonlit Avian Dance" Secret Pack to save 60 SR! You can use any two Lyrilusc Rank 1 XYZ monsters, doesn't have to be exactly those listed nor they have to be different.

 

So, in total, you can save up to 660 SR and 60 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. If you have any questions, feel free to ask. Have fun in Master Duel!

deck_excerpt: You thought you XYZ or synchro with that monster. Ha Ha Ha it has a predator counter you fool it level 1 !!!
deck_description:
This is Predaplant bystial. It is the base Predaplant engine ( incluing the fallen of albaz cards) with the bystial to provide the ablity to put card back into while getting a draw.

The main line go as this. summon predaplant Ambulomelides ( Amb, search predaplant bylisp it you don't have it in hand or haven't activated it this turn over wise get something else like Bufolicula if not in hand or not used (Buf), Drosophyllum Hydra if you need something to discard, or predaprime or predaplanting. then use Amb second effect to summon cobra, search branded fusion. activate it, send fallen + bystial lubellion, summon albion, use albion banish Amb and fallen for lubellion, use lubellion discarding byslip for mirror jade, using Amb and the albaz, use byslip and get Buf, use buf to fusion lubellion and cobra for dragostaplia, summon bystial lube, active branded regain. set anything you want to ( if your worried about nib hold your quick play fusion yes even super if need be. ) use ablion to set banishment.

That is the main combo.

few tips for the deck,

1.  hydra effect in grave will banish a predaplant to reduce a monsters attack by 500. this will trigger regain allowing to shuffle and draw a card. it is a quick effect too. 

2. use quick play fusion spell to dodge effect when needed. as such when ever you can place triantis, which can be use a fusion as if it on the feild in the scale, also allow buf to be use from there too. 

3. this deck can chain block all effects but the second effect of amb, and the branded fusion. use this to use advantage. triantis counter placements can be deadly in this way. 

4. triphoverutum hit real hard, and when using predaprime can use a dark on the other field making up for his big cost.

deck_excerpt: When the fires burn so bright that they're almost overwhelming, there's always a latent darkness that's potent enough to snuff it out.
deck_description:
Another update due to the new banlist. Sad to see that the Sinful Spoils engine didn't allow this deck to get a pseudo-Slifer style effect for controlling the board and interrupting plays but it is what it is. Magikuriboh got buffed to half now which is generally a boon for this deck (though it's more of a buff for generic splashes of Dark Magician)- but it for sure means we get to include another half point card in our arsenal. Since the format is expected to be pretty... disgusting with the number of legal engines that generate an obsene amount of advantage, my deck profiles during this season will lean more on the casual side rather than compettive. If you want my competitive picks then look no further than anything incorporating Snake-Eyes, Rescue-Ace, Chaos-Attributed Decks, and Albaz piles. Enough pandering about that stuff though, onto the deck profile.

It's been brought to my attention that pilots of Dark Magician have been having a hard time navigating the lines of the deck and tripping up on the opener and midgames. If you have any difficulty with the decks I make feel free to contact me at @veissalthen on Discord and I'll try to provide you with replays and/or sample games and testhands to help you get used to the deck. My builds are curated in a specific way so when they're modified slightly to shake-up the gameplan significantly, results can definitely be expected to vary. Please review the lines listed here in the article as points of reference so that you might find yourself comfortable with the build first. With that in mind, this iteration of DM will be focusing primarily on a more controlling and tempo-managment game rather than my Spell-Heavy counterparts. This is mostly just due to the comfort trap cards tend to provide for Trinity duelists rather than having a hand full of plays and enablers. The overall lines remain the same, you just won't have as much gas as before. Reference previous builds for those variations.

Chronicle Sorceress still isn't here. Please come home.


- Difficulty -
★★★☆☆
With Dark Burning Magic still banned at this time, the deck's not entirely unga bunga insta-win, but it doesn't exactly feature any real complexities when it comes to finding routes to winning games. The difficulty with this deck lies entirely with managing one's hand, GY, and copies of Dark Magician either between the Deck, GY, or Hand and knowing just how many are where. To get the absolute most out of the deck, you'll likely need to be mindful of where Dark Magician Girl is and how to get Combination in rotation. Resolving Illusion is great and all, but remember that our main deck monsters aren't the greatest here like most other decks you'll encounter, so resolving a search each turn and doing nothing with it will set you further behind compared to a typical turn in modern Trinity.

 - Consistency -
★★★★☆
Illusion, Servant, and Rod all communicate with one another very well and so long as you can find any one of those pieces in the opener, then you're basically golden for the remainder of the duel. If you're familiar with the Orcust Trinity then this can be seen largely the same way. As such we have a myriad of ways of accessing Illusion of Chaos (even more so than Rod who is our primary starter since it grabs all of the S/Ts we actually care about). Cycling Rod every turn with Illusion back up is a double search that snowballs rather quickly. We aren't as consistent in this build solely because we have more Trap Cards this time around but Trap Tracks isn't exactly a brick. It doubles as a way of putting Rod in the GY and getting us to impactful backrow.

- Sackiness -
★★★★☆
Unfortunately this build isn't on very many Semi and Co-Forbidden cards, so the powerlevel lies strictly within the realm of DM's capabilities. While we do have blowouts with Dark Burning Attack and Dark Magic Attack within their respective gamestates, neither being quick-play is a serious downside when it comes to Trinity tempo. Regardless, Soul Servant's GY effect on average drawing 2 cards with a maxiumum of 4 is pretty hilarious and downright unfair (in a better archetype). If you want to upgrade the sackiness factor, look into jamming more Pointed cards, Bystials, and relevant backrow to steal games. Reduce the skill required to execute DM combos and you'll reduce the skill required to win randomly via a topdeck, frankly speaking.

- Viability -
★★★★★
Chaos Attributed deck with decades' worth of support. The deck also plays nicely with reliable backrow, nukes, and can play Bystials of its own when they're sided in against them. While I wouldn't consider Dark Magician to be META, it is without a doubt viable enough to be played in virtually any format that doesn't feature Normal Summon Fallen of Albaz.


Pros:

  • Snowball: You rack up advantage pretty quickly once you get going with this strategy. Between all of the layers of protection and nuance regarding the disruption lines on top of all of the means of searching from over a decade's worth of support? It's honestly difficult not to win after taking the lead.

  • Runick Engine: The advantages provided through the currently legal Runick line-up are a bit concerning, at least when it comes to control decks that don't just turtle behind a Link Monster. Being able to chain any one of them in order to either get a free Link Material for Lyna or Dharc; or protection from destruction; or just generating a token to convert later while also blanking a monster/attack in the same way Galaxy-Eyes Photon Dragon would; on top of just their natural effects is frankly a little silly for a package that doesn't tax the Main Deck in any meaningful way. It also goes without saying that being able to just randomly banish cards from your opponent's deck in a Highlander format is incredibly broken on so many levels as most decks these days require specific cards to function and do not feature ways of recovering said banished cards. You may honestly just win games through the inclusion of this engine alone, so if you find yourself with it, just know that you've not only gotten insurance, but also some pretty potent plusses under The Dark Magicians Fusion.

  • Comeback Potential: Just having Illusion, Rod, Controlling the Dark Magician, or even just having Soul Servant in the GY during mid-to-late game will keep you in the game regardless of how things are going. Just don't play too zealously into something like a Trickstar Candina!

  • Rewarding Ceiling: While a lot of the early lines are pretty straightforward, most of the complexities with the archetype as a whole come from the usage of cards in tandem with one another. As opposed to early TCG builds where you kind of just drew cards and hoped it was enough to combo or amass a handtrap/backrow advantage, in Trinity, you'll be much more rewarded for your mastery of the cards at your disposal and how to best navigate the board you're dealt with or expecting. At times the pressure can be nigh suffocating from this deck.

 

Cons:

  • Possible to Brick: Unlike its TCG counterpart, due to the nature of the format, DM can't exactly take advantage of so much deck-thinning and draw power and while some cards like the Spellbook engine would help with the cycling process a bit, they will always be setting you a turn behind and adding more additional cards to cycle through in the long run. A brick doesn't necessarily equate to your searchers and passing, it's more of the unplayable circumstances of drawing... all of the Dark Magicians and having no way of summoning them. Hence why we've got some backrow to fall back on and ways to cheat him out in the event of a crisis.

  • Bond Between Teacher and Student: This particular list makes great use of Dark Magician Girl and cards concerning her (without playing the Magician Girl archetype of course) and as amazing as the cards surrounding her are, she herself is terrible to use. You'll be wanting to bin her whenever possible or simply control her when under gamestates like Magician's Combination. There's even a cheeky setup concerning Brain Controll (or Big Eye) and using her as Xyz material to go into Dhampir Sheridan. All of those applications aside, she (and her Signature Spell) aren't that great and don't feel that great to have until necessary for certain combos.

  • Stat-Checked: If faced with too many monsters that are 3000 ATK/DEF or above you might run into a brick wall sometimes. You can tech in the Honests to get around this a bit better, but you'll need to hard draw those. Mahad can clear all things that are DARK and Apprentice can help the respective targets clear certain thresholds but most of the time those will be one use situations. Fortunately you can use Soul Servant to stack them from the GY to the top of deck for one final use.

With introductions over, let's get into the setups you'll want to seek seek more.

 



OPENERS

Thanks to all of the years of support this archetype has received it has gained a number of searchers and retroactive searchers to help boost its consistency and lines of play to be very reliable which is a massive boon when it comes to limited formats like this one. Generally, any starter will net you the same gamestate no matter what goes down; however, there are some combinations of 2 or more cards that do require a bit more setup.

  • Manju & Senju: Opening one of these cards enables you to grab Illusion of Chaos (or Sauravis if you already have it) then search Magicians' Souls. Using Souls you'll want to setup your GY with either Mana to protect your plays going down the line or DM/DMG to establish them early and get them in rotation for the later stages of the game. Then you'll pivot into either Dharc or Lyna. With Dharc you can grab Magikuriboh and use it during that same battle phase (or main phase later) to summon a Dark M agician immediately, Witch of the Black Forest if you have particularly greedy setup lines to go for in future turns with fusion plays or revival, or simply Magician's Rod who is the best starter in the deck when combined with other cards in the strategy and it's not even close! As for Lyna, Witchcrafter Golem Aruru will be our primary find; however, Diviner of the Herald isn't particularly bad either. The reason why is below.

  • Diviner of the Herald: Using its effect to send, we'll pitch Arc Light from our Extra Deck to make it a Level 6 tuner, then we'll use Arc Light to grab Illusion of Chaos from the deck. Using Illusion, we'll pick up Magicians' Souls and send the appropriate targets like within the Manju & Senju lines to the GY to summon it directly from the hand. Then we'll Synchro Summon itno Fortune Lady Every. This card being a Level 7 who revives itself and answers the board during the SP is very handy for Rank 7 lines and getting rid of pesky monsters. It's worth noting that her banish effect to bring herself back does come up in this deck so don't use it willy-nilly. Banishing Souls is fine, but everything else in this list definitely is not. Use it within moderation as her effect can be used even on turns where she wasn't sent to the GY since it checks during each of their End Phase's. If you happen to need Rod and have a usable S/T at your disposal, you can summon her back, then use that S/T to tribute her and add back the Magician's Rod at EP to start your turn with your primary searcher. Very handy indeed.

  • Magician's Rod: This card probably has the highest ceiling regarding its uses since now, with Illusion of Chaos, it can search the entire archetype and its support including adding Dark Magician to the hand when necessary. You may also want to (if on the second turn or later) Link it off into Clara & Rushka so that during the opponent's turn, when you activate an S/T, you can tribute the link to add Rod back to hand. One line I like to particularly setup involves using it as fusion material for The Dark Magicians by grabbing Secrets of Dark Magic, that way in the event that the Fusion would be destroyed and I have a S/T I can use, I'd usually tribute away the Dark Magician girl to recycle Rod for next turn. You can also go for some pretty devastating Bond Between Teacher and Student setups when going second (or later in the game) to nuke your opponent's S/Ts or Monsters. It was this particular line of play that actually winded up getting Dark Burning Magic banned here. Oops.

The majority of the time you'll want to stick to opening with one of these cards but if you happen to find yourself opening things like just DM or ways to him, it's still fine to cycle your respective S/Ts and support him as necessary. He's still the star of the deck and it's important to make sure you keep up your advantage until you can snowball the game out of controll.


MIDGAME

This is where most games can end for you since the deck can swarm pretty decently after being setup or be rather controlling between Aruru and Mana being a devastating duo.

  • Bystial Baldrake: This card challenges most strategies with just its D.D. Crow effect; however, also being able to bin Dark Magicians, Rods, or resolved Manju/Senjus comes in handy for its tribute cost while still representing a lot of pressure. Additionally, it's a Dragon for a potential Fusion play into Dragon Knights and finally, it is a Level 6 that can be used to make Sheridan or Wollow to completely turn the game on its head proactively rather than reactively. If you can only banish out of your GY, then Servant, Mahad, and the Ritual Package should be fine banishes without any notable lasting consequences. You lose 1 draw for banishing out Palladiums but that's a sacrifice you have to make sometimes. The new addition from AGOV Seed-Spitting Siblings serves much of the same purpose. While we don't have many cards that can target our own Monsters in this deck, having it up with DM doubles as a Baldrake that hits ANY Special Summon, not just the Baldrake ones.

  • Eternal Soul: Don't flip this card too early without insurance, it immediately puts a target on itself and players usually try to remove it when its face-up every time. That said, it can revive DMs for free and search out your one-sided Heavy Storm whenever you want. Use it to secure a lead or establish one. The safest setup to use it under midgame is definitely when controlling The Dark Magicians fusion monster, since if Eternal Soul leaves, the fusion would be destroyed but still float into the master and student, ultimately not setting you too far behind.

  • Soul Servant: This card's GY effect is rather potent and is virtually unrivaled when it comes to Unlimited power cards in Trinity Format. You'll usually be resolving it to draw two; however, with this build it's possible to draw up to four cards naturally from this effect- and we play TWO copies. The most important things to note about the stacking (and not searching) effect is that you can use it during the EP of your opponent's turn to rig your next draw and the fact that this card can stack cards from your GY to the top of the deck which is very, very potent in a limited format. Don't forget this as it might save you when piloting the deck!

Should the game not end at this point and you find yourself in a complex, mind-boggling gamestate then you're probably going to want one of the following closers.


LATEGAME & CLOSERS

  • Dark Magician the Dragon Knight & Eternal Soul: This combination is really rough to deal with, especially since S/T removal is very limited in Trinity, so if this is established you have virtually won. DMtDK is treated as DM so it can be revived by Eternal Soul and is constantly under its protection, additionally, Eternal Soul is protected by DMtDK's continuous effect, making this a really rough situation to navigate for the opponent in most cases. Additionally, since DMtDK is treated as DM, it works with the field spell Magician's Salvation and Magician's Combination so even something like a DMG can represent DMtDK coming back over and over while protecting said cards in the process. This card is a monster and needs to be respected when properly established.

  • Magician's Combination: Probably the most underrated support card this deck has at its disposal. You tag out your DM/DMG to their counterpart and negate any card or effect (just not the activation so no Damage Step shenanigans). Once the opponent has had enough and decides to blow up Combination, it even has a revenge effect to clear a card on their side of the field. You can also force this effect yourself with Timaeus the United Dragon and Magicians' Souls turning those plays into removal.

  • Signature Move: Though these cards are often considered bad and I even think so most of the time myself, I cannot understate how potent their effects are when they resolve. In all of my history playtesting this deck in any iteration, the games in which the Signature Attacks of the duo have resolved have always resulted in my win. Whether that be the easily accessed Dark Magic Attack or the trickier to pull off Dark Burning Attack (though you can access it easier with Bond), the signature moves can really just blow away opponents regardless of their deck type and cut the game shorter than what they might have been expecting.

 


Since the lines from the archetype itself are rather consistent, the deck can be easy to get started with, but might take a bit to get used to and master; however, it's usability allows a great deal of customizability to cater to most tech choices like Dragonmaids or the legal Bystials to establish DMtDK easier or SPYRAL to do Master Plan setups with Magicians' Souls. Regardless, here's a handful of ideas just to throw your way should you aim to adjust this baseline into something more focused elsewhere:

Viability Boosters: Kashtira Monsters & Birth | Magician of Dark Illusion (more consistent with Runicks than its own archetype) | Bystials (more Dragon Knights and Rank 6s) | Protecting Spirit Loagaeth | Mana Dragon Zimitron (Runicks do the protection better, this is more so just to loop Servant) | Blazing Cartesia, the Virtuous | Rescue-ACE (You can summon Cavalry with like every hand and represent draws with DMs Fusion) | Witchcrafter

General Purpose: Magician of Chaos, High Ritual Art, & Chaos Form, Chicken Game, Destined Rivals, Traptrix Engine, Fiend Engine, Dragonmaid

I'm sure you might've noticed but this version of the build doesn't actually feature very much in the way of gameplan changes despite the modifications done to the main and Extra Deck. Just goes to show how potent the individual cards can be when it comes to promoting and establishing those wincons faster, or just outright being them by themselves. It does rub me the wrong way a bit, but there isn't much to be done about it besides adapt. Dark Magician is timeless and with more support coming in AGOV we're bound to adapt to an even more disgusting level as the card quality increases. Hopefully it just doesn't reach a point where the only Dark Magician cards a DM Deck will play are simply Souls and Illusion of Chaos.

50 Card Deck = 4 Points with 4p used.
1p Magician's Rod (Extra Copy)
1p Soul Servant (Extra Copy)
1p Witchcrafter Golem Aruru
.5p Magikuriboh
.5p Trap Tracks

I'm currently working on a Dark Magician of Chaos version of the deck that will be my primary focus with Dark Magicians until we get Chronicle Sorceress. Expect this to be the definitive version of my Starter Deck for them in Trinity until further notice. Adjust Spell/Traps as necessary with each format of course. Good luck with the upcoming format.

deck_name: Fun with Faithful Flips [Trinity Format | October '23]
deck_excerpt: A for-fun strategy inspired by NobodyTCG (LargLad) and Hamtaro from the Trinity server.
deck_description:
This isn't quite the Chaos variant you might've been expecting when seeing Magician of Faith. Nah, this one's more focused primarily on Flip Monsters and cycling decent-to-great Spell Cards. For that sorta vibe, I'd recommend looking into Shaddolls, Thunder Dragons, or Orcust with the entire Bystial engine incorporated for a pretty neat iteration of Chaos Control. As the tagline suggests, this deck takes inspiration mostly from NobodyTCG and Hamtaro, two people that I knew from Trinity's Discord server that had a thing for incorporating strategies from Goat Format into Trinity (for better or worse). They were always fun to see, so here's my take on the formula as well, without being a blatant copycat.

The strategy takes advantage of the fact that Magician of Faithfulness is Unbound, meaning we get to play three copies of it at no cost to us. This doubles a boon for the sake of building up 3/5 slots towards a Point on top of being able to reference itself for its own effect (which we should be doing pretty regularly, unless we don't already have OG MoF in rotation).


- Difficulty -
★★★☆☆
While this deck isn't exactly hard to play, I'd more so argue that it's a challenge to compete with. Since our main deck monsters aren't the best, we'll want to beat up the opponent (irl) in order to nerf them to our level and be on the same playing ground. Focus on cycling your spells as best you can and pivot the Extra Deck where appropriate. While there's frankly insane strategies that can be curated right now in Trinity (like that TCG Unchained Jumpscare that happened last season), any investment that isn't a board wipe usually is considered in our favor as 1 for 1 trades with bad cards is always a plus and battle is usually the most sought-after out to Flip Monsters.

 - Consistency -
★★☆☆☆
Not terribly consistent. You play the hand you're dealt and hope for the best. We have plenty of tutors and potent S/Ts so it's not like you'll brick per se, you just won't have a crazy opener.

- Sackiness -
★★★☆☆
Monster Stealing is the main asset of sacking with this deck. If you want to sack more then pivot Chaos!

- Viability -
★☆☆☆☆
This strategy is entirely for fun so play it with that purpose.

45 Card Deck = 3 Points with 3p used.
1p Pot of Greed
1p Change of Heart
.5p Mind Control
.5p Titanocider

I'll consider beefing this baby up to be a properly somewhat viable deck in the future but it'll be on the backburner until I figure out Crusadia.

Please remember to have fun and enjoy whatever you do for your pasttime... and be kind to your opponents! >:D

deck_excerpt: Wearing it better than Total Defense Shogun since 2014.
deck_description:
I'm not typically a fan of Monster Mash decks in Highlander formats, but Superheavy Samurai has always been a pet deck of mine in Trinity Format. While I think that's substantially better and more potent Monster Mash decks, this archetype performs well enough on its own thanks to the inclusion of the latest waves of support. I used to primarily focus on Wagon and Soulpeacemaker but the new cards elevate things to a level of silliness that it's almost recommended to avoid those cards entirely just because they've been powercrept. That said, the lines from the new cards do require discards so we'll still be leaning on some of the old ones to get by wherever we can.


- Difficulty -
★★☆☆☆
Despite being a combo-oriented deck and you WILL be rewarded for thinking ahead, the majority of your hands will not be curated and will be primarily composed of random monsters. You only have control over searching Superheavy Samurai Monsters and EARTH Machines in this deck. Handtraps and backrow? You're outta luck my friend.

 - Consistency -
★★★★☆
Consistent enough to find what you need. For your opener routes. This is an inherent advantage over standard Monster Mash decks in Trinity since they aren't usually archetypal and backed by a niche support line.

- Sackiness -
★★☆☆☆
Games can be stolen with the Synchros, Dingirsu, or just the classic Soulbuster Gauntlet attack; however, these sacks are just entirely expressions of skill and have nothing to do with luck-sacking the opponent. Every victory rewarded that wasn't a 1-handtrap wonder is earned.The main sack we're running in this deck is ironically unironically Unity. Trust me.

- Viability -
★★★☆☆
My winrate with Superheavy Samurai has been consistently positive when testing them against new players and veterans alike of the format and that was before we got their latest wave of support. The new support enables us to do builds that can lean more on powerful Spell/Traps solely because Steam Train King is much easier to outright summon now, thus allowing us to cleanse our GY of such cards and return to machine.

Despite being a pet deck of mine, I won't be doing a long write-up for this deck. Just know that your main starters are: Wakaushi, Soulpeacemaker, and Wagon. Make the appropriate Synchro depending on your own preference. If going 1st, I recommend going for Shanao, Dragster, Ballista, or Gigant X. When going second you can blowout the opponent with Shutendoji and Steam Train King, but there's nothing wrong with a low-investment Benkei OTK attempt. More technical gamestates will reward key usages of Masurawo, Susanowo, Sheridan, Soulbang Cannon, and Flutist.

Comeback plays lie in Battleball, Gearbox -> Anchor Drill -> summon Drill and go into Ding, Revolution Synchron, and Railroad Stampede.

Recovery comes from Tunneler, Wakaushi, Vernusylph... Awakening Forests, Samurai Scales, Samurai Constable, Gigagloves, Machina Overdrive, and Prepped Defense.

50 Card Deck = 4 Points with 4p used.
1p Superheavy Samurai Prodigy Wakaushi (Extra Copy)
1p Superheavy Samurai Prodigy Wakaushi (Extra Copy)
1p Superheavy Samurai Soulpeacemaker (Extra Copy)
1p Superheavy Samurai Motorbike (Extra Copy)

Not terribly competitive but can be quite fun to play with all the bizarre restrictions this archetype has. Warlord Susanowo is also one of my favorite Synchros of all time to use in Trinity Format. Not because it's particularly good, just simply because it creates so many interesting gamestates.

deck_excerpt: Where Light And Darkness Work Together
deck_description:
BASE COMBO:

Opening Hand: Core, Chimera, 2 Power Cards, 1 Irrelevant Spell/Trap

1. Normal Summon Core To Activate Effect To Search Realm

2. Activate Realm And Search Claw With It

3. Pitch Claw To Search Horizon

4. Activate Horizon To Dump Chimera And Attachment Cybern; Add Cannon; Dump Cyber End Dragon

5.Activate Chimera Grave Effect To Dump Keel

6. Pitch Cannon To Search Chimera

7. Activate Realm's Secondary Effect To Normal Summon Chimera

8. Activate Chimera And Discard A Spell/Trap; Add Power Bond

9. Activate Power Bond And Fuse From Grave And Field Thanks To Chimera; Fusion Summon Cyberdarkness Dragon

10. Equip Cyber End To Cyberdarkness Upon Summon

11. Tribute Equipped Cyberdarkness; Contact Fusion Into Cyberdark End Dragon

12. Activate Cyberdark End Effect To Equip Attachment Cybern

 POWER PLAY:

Assuming Your Power Cards Are Machine Duplication And Cyberdark Invasion; Activate Machine Duplication To Target Core And Special Summon 2 Cyber Dragons, Then Overlay Into Nova And Then Infinity, Absorb Core For Safety Sake. Set Invasion. End Your Turn.

OPPONENT's POSSIBLE MOVES:

Suppose They Bait You With Lightning Storm; Infinity Negates It

Thinking They Are Safe Now They Summon A Monster Or Activate A Continous Spell And Try To Combo; Activate Invasion To Pop Their Key Piece And Send Cybern To Grave; Cybern Grave Effect Special Summons Cyberdarkness From Grave; Cyberdarkness Equips From Grave To Give You An Additional Negate.

deck_excerpt: Blow stuff up then XYZ/Synchro your way with level 8s to victory!
deck_description:
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
Hello fellow Blind Second Player! 
 
Are you tired of long combos, losing to time, and frying your brain with the complexity of Yugioh gameplay? Want to play a no-brainer, unga-bunga, unreasonably expensive beatdown deck that blows your opponent's board up and turbos out gigantic boss monsters? 8-AXIS OTK is the deck for you!!!
 
This deck is relatively simple to play, so there will be no in-depth article for this strategy. For 8-AXIS OTK, you simply obliterate your opponent's board with board breakers like Lightning Storm, Raigeki, Change of Heart and Harpie's Feather Duster, making way for your level 8 monsters to special summon themselves to the field. When level 8 monsters are on the field, you have the choice to either synchro summon (if you have Blackwing Sharnga or Assault Synchron) or XYZ summon into your rank 8 of choice. 
 
In most cases, you will not finish off your opponent's lifepoints in one turn, but you can greatly simplify the gamestate with your boardbreakers and beatsticks. In such a situation, Baronne, Chengying and a 4 material Zeus is often enough to win games by themselves. 
 
That's all you need to know for this strategy. NOW HOP ON MASTERDUEL LADDER, BLIND SECOND AND BLOW UP YOUR OPPONENT'S BOARD WITH 8-AXIS OTK!!!

GLHF Duelist!

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
