deck_excerpt: Not a deck profile, but I can't upload articles for Trinity so this will have to suffice. Reupload in articles at your behest.
deck_description:
This article raises a discussion point that I feel like is often ignored (and was often ignored even during the time I was actively participating in Trinity) concerning the fundamental gameplay of it and how tempo swings without the reliance of specific outs, counters, or archetypal dominance can often be rewarded. This discussion stems solely from the principle of the 3 Effect Monster Summon Limit per turn and not so much deckbuilding by itself; however, the ideas presented here should put a spotlight on things that are often overlooked and misunderstood to be happening during games, especially when it comes to conversion of value and simply conversations between cards between a player's turns.

Full disclosure: Since I can't upload articles directly to this site, this is going up as a deck profile with the article attached. Anyone who has the capability of uploading articles for Trinity feel free to canabalize this piece and reupload at your leisure. I will unlist this in the event that transpires. Just remember to give credit. ^^

The restricting factor of the 3 Effect Monster Summon limit per turn is one of the defining features of Trinity Format and what makes it separate from other alternative formats. While it does create quite the bottleneck situation for jamming in as many powerful cards and plays within the same turn and ultimately makes trumping the 2nd or even more pivotal- 3rd summon with interaction rather game-deciding at times, it franky comes with the territory and is something that a veteran generally learns to respect rather than going blindly all-in all the time. Due to the nature of the summon limit, plays are often cut off from being at their full potential, even those that bear the greatest resemblance to their TCG counterparts (or in some cases are quite literally just direct imports from Advanced to here). In my time as a semi-competitive player and analyst of the format, I always noticed how cards that stuck around to convert into Extra Deck plays (generally things like Accesscode Talker, Borrelsword, and even the lower bound of Knightmare Unicorn) actively turned into a snowball regardless of the associated strategy, deck type, or advantage state of the players. This is primarily because regardless of how great one's deck actually performs, in the sea of being expected to win or lose games primarily through battle damage, you can at least rest assured that you have a buffer to protect you from being outright OTKed (and often times regularly drawing out games to Turn 4 and beyond when interaction is had). In the case of low ATK power strategies this is even more apparent as they simply just don't deal enough damage to put the pressure on, instead representing threats in another way. This is part of why it's fine to use LP as a resource; however, this also introduces the factor that one can just use the turns themselves as a resource, no?

As previously stated, the preservation of a monster(s) going into your turn to start with that don't actively take away from your 3 Summons for the turn are a boon that can often lead to a tempo swing so great it casts a hard shadow over any card advantage. Speaking from experience, I knew this to be the case with decks that played on both players turns or featured floaters and resource loops to maintain field presence even when cards were lost. In my case this was primarily showcased with my favorite deck in Shaddolls but even without the advantages provided from such a strategy, resolving things that would protect your monsters or simply disrupt a play from the opponent on their turn (even if it didn't necessaily prevent their monsters from occupying the board) would still preserve your monsters in the end.

Lightning Rods
The art of misdirection is rather deadly in a resource-driven card game.

Since this tempo swing exists, wouldn't it then make sense to put greater value on cards that can effectively interact with the opponent in a meaningfully-adjacent way? Well, kind of.  Sadly with this game, all cards aren't created equal. A card like Blockout Curtain for example fufills the preservation topic in question but serves as one of the worst buffers by far (though the GY effect can be cheeky as a counter to some destruction-based strategies). The advantage of cards that are Continuous is that their conversion can actually be directly extended between turns. Therefore, it would make the most sense to instead play cards that either generate continuous advantage over time or put the opponent on a clock in the continuous slot rather than rely solely on redirecting abilities such as this one. For example, for as slow as cards like Wave Motion Cannon and Cauldron of the Old Man are to start out, they will put the opponent on a timer regardless and only actively punish the user if they're using the effects greedily. With a target placed on such cards, the opponent is thereby forced to close out the game faster or resort to wasting removal on said cards which don't even need to necessarily contribute to a burn-specific gameplan. You regardless have protected your other Spell/Traps and/or in some cases of omni-targeting destruction, have saved yourself a headache down the line. With one of the most referenced outs to Spell/Trap Removals existing in Knightmare Phoenix, you have effectively made the opponent give up their board, summons, and a Discard to out a card that was never your win condition to begin with.

This is a much more elegant usage of a redirection tactic and makes the errors lie mostly within the opponent's court for misplays as their decisions will ultimately decide their clock, turns to kill, and how best to convert what they have into an answer when the time feels appropriate.

Preservation of Field
Monster Conversions are always valuable.

As mentioned before with my addressal of Shaddolls, there are inherent strengths provided to anyone who can actually preserve their monsters between turns. This is generally taken for granted by most players who only look at the game as starters and end-boards rather than as a card game altogether and often can lead to easily-avoided defeat circumstances. This is generally evidenced in losses where decks that can easily pump out Rank 4s or Synchro 8s aren't running Abyss Dweller nor Crimson Blader in matches where they would only stand to benefit from it. Instead choosing to simply blindly attack and destroy cards until something ultimately sticks. While I agree that removing monsters by battle is effecient and a clean +1 per monster defeated (on top of anything that was used to go into it), it is a very easy bottleneck to deal with and makes cards like Mirror Force criminally underrated for just stealing games. This then begs the question of what sorts of cards to preserve one's field are the most effective then? Well, cards are always getting released and powercrept out and while this isn't entirely intended to be a showcase of specific cards to be running in your matches, I'll at least highlight some ideas for preservation tactics.

The aforementioned Mirror Forces are great for swinging a game instantly and has counterparts that can trade one for one or in some cases outright take control of the monster, but it does ultimately come down to building up where the faults of a deck might lie. Blue-Eyes strategies as an example will actively command the board with large monsters that have some of the highest attack to try and out consistently, making the process generally exhausting to deal with. It's for this reason that they don't necessarily benefit from running battle-stops as much as they would removal-stops. It shouldn't be so much as a protect-the-castle strategy might commit but you can definitely understand the benefit of maintaining a 3k+ Beatstick on the board to start your turn with- bonus points if that monster has a level and be converted into an even more powerful Rank 8.

For most decks I would argue this isn't really the case and protections of this variety (barring exactly Forbidden Lance and similar cards) should be avoided in favor of blanket battle-stops or ressurection tricks. This is obviously prominent in the Mirror Forces but what about for opponents that would be safe and convert things into a removal monster to get rid of the backrow in question first before attacking? Well, then you'd need something chainable right? Obviously we aren't going to run something like Fake Trap to preserve our cards here, no, but unironically committing to something like a Threatening Roar does go a long way, especially after the opponent has already gone through lengths to commit several summons into an expected board-clear with their battle phase. Denying them attacks on your monsters keeps them around and forces strictly effect removal to deal with them going into your next turn. It also outright denies on-attack effects altogether. Waboku is in a similar boat but lacks the on-attack prevention, it instead can be used for triggering your own on-attack related effects without losing your monsters (i.e. War Rocks). This is a rather underrated method of keeping your advantage and doesn't really matter when in the game it's around so long as you aren't in a top decking situation to begin with. Denying your opponent the ability to make clean outs to your board while ultimately preserving most if not all of your monsters will always be to your benefit due to the Summon Limit restriction of the format.

Lastly, this can be achieved with blinking effects like your Interdimensional Matter Transporter type of effects. While I would generally run Book of Moon,  Sol & Luna, or Forbidden Lance over that card specfically, this does actually carry some substantial weight in the form of a Monster Effect that can do the same thing. Such is the case for cards like the Bunny Ear Enthusiast who can preserve your own monsters and itself or simply be a Wind-Up Rabbit but also blink out your Opponent's Monster until your next turn (similar to Timebreaker Magician or PSY-Framelord Zeta if you're familiar with those cards). D.D. Seeker deserves an honorable mention as well but can be messy to plan around, especially in the case of dealing with interaction; however, that card can ultimately preserve more monsters than Bunny in the long-term. A card that fits this bill and the Waboku category is Ichiroku's Ledger Book in case you were looking for something of that variety.

Using cards like these can often be completely ruled out for being "gimmicky" or "neutral/negative" in terms of immediate advantage when it comes to snapshot gamestates; however, the most important things to consider are the strengths and weakenesses of the strategies you're intending to play. While I imagine there's all sorts of legal burn FTKs or ways to rip your opponent's entire hand before they get the opportunity to play around, you're objectively the most likely to encounter loses due to 60% or more of it being from Battle Damage in Trinity Format. Modern players focus a lot on effeciency and value and not time to kill nor what to actually do when you are bricked into oblivion with a hand full of Garnets. These preservation tactics shouldn't be overlooked solely because they aren't abiding by the formula you might find popular in the format or Advanced. Trinity Format is a very different game with a very different ruleset. While it's fair to assess that wins can be handed to someone on a silver platter for running objectively broken and toxic cards, there's nothing to be said for near-equal matchups between pilots who understand their decks besides misplays and outplays. Adding more to the table to swing such moments undeniably in your favor should be pursued, not avoided and would frankly invite more to the table when deck building and discussing the topic of what makes a Staple a Staple.

At the end of the day, the cards exist to be used. Cards that are generally quite middling or "whatever" quality at the time of their printing may give your exponentially high returns when put into practice in this 3 Summon Format. You don't lose anything from experimenting with practice and you only stand to gain if you invetiably win on the backs of said preservation tactics. This also totally allows you to pump out Link 4s and 5s pretty regularly like some decks such as Traptrix, Ghostrick, and Altergeist are capable of doing despite objectively not being Link-Spam combo decks.

 

Thanks for reading!

deck_excerpt: The power of Rituals and Synchro monsters cannot be stopped!
deck_description:
A union of the incredible Centurions and the stunning Silenforce!

A typical endboard on Turn 1 is making Legatia and having Summoned Skull + Novox + Barrier + Stand-Up on the field, with Primera called back to a Spell & Trap zone in end phase. Legatia offers extra protection for Novox to survive whatever your opponent does, while Barrier protects Legatia as well. You can then on Turn 2 use Skull Guardian's effect to negate an opponent's card or effect and bring Primera into a Monster Zone. This will trigger Stand Up allowing you to Synchro into Crimson Dragon using Skull and Novox. Then when your opponent does something else, use Crimson Dragon to target Legatia and summon Sifr or Blazar Dragon, giving you further negates and similarly large bodies comparable to Skull Guardian. Chances are you may have Effect Sauravis as well, giving you more tools or a body to ritual summon using into another Skull Guardian.

You can of course replace one of these with King Calamity, but I'm not fond of locking my opponent out of playing YuGiOh.

Many hands  also give you easy ways to synchro into Baronne or Chaos Angel. If you open Diviner + Stand Up or another Centurion card that can fetch Trudea, you can make Chaos Angel with the dual effect.

deck_excerpt: Fire Princess FTK ft. Genex Ally Birdman + Imperial Iron Wall + Spring of Rebirth
deck_description:
Greetings! It looks like a fiery princess is rising from her ashes once more, thanks to a birdman. Let's be careful!

 

 

Gameplan

1) Special Summon Fire Princess with Saryuja. Make sure there is at least one monster from Main Deck, different from Princess.

2) Activate Temple of the Kings + Imperial Iron Wall + Spring of Rebirth.

3) Return that monster, which will be Panda as an example, to bring forth first Birdman. Then, bring forth second Birdman by returning first one. This is a continuous loop because Iron Wall prevents Birdmen from banishing.

4) By repeating #3 while Princess + Spring are around, you can burn your opponent to death.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Genex Ally Birdman" can be found within "Elemental Exchanges" Secret Pack to save 60 SR!

deck_excerpt: Number 43 FTK ft. Mythical Beast Cerberus
deck_description:
So, you might have heard of Endymion decks, where they excel at utilizing Spell Counters for big plays. Endymions were also known alongside their Mythical Beasts and Cerberus is one of them, seen in "Side Deck". Yet, did you know its OG variant was actually completely different? In this deck, you will see it.

 

 

Gameplan

1) Special Summon "Mythical Beast Cerberus" as early as possible to boost its ATK whenever you play a spell and place Spell Counter on it. Here are the possible scenarios...

  • In the very beginning, if you have opened with Monk and pulled out Panda, that means Ancient can bring forth Cerberus without breaking any plans or Extra Deck summons.
  • If you have only started with Panda, that means you have to rely on some of Endymions:
    • If you don't have none of Endymions but "Spell Power Mastery", tutor one of them. "Servant of Endymion" can pull out Cerberus from your deck while "Reflection of Endymion" can pull out Cerberus from your hand. Choose it wisely.
    • When you have used one of their abilities, you need to alleviate your board space issues for Extra Deck summons by playing "Monster Recovery" and targeting on either Servant or Reflection. After playing "Monster Recovery", don't forget to spare one Pendulum Zone for ME-PSY-YA, which is essential for "Primal Seed" setup.
    • If you don't like any of these options, remove Endymion cards in addition to "Monster Recovery" and either add "Double Summon" or "Trismagistus" to Special Summon Cerberus whenever possible. You can check them in "Side Deck". The drawback is that you might have to play lots of spells to boost Cerberus, which can take more time than usual.
    • If you still don't like anything being offered, you can Special Summon Cerberus with Saryuja but prepare for APM actions with "Primal Seed" setup, which will be explained later on.

2) XYZ Summon Number 13 by using 2 x Level 1 monsters as materials. Then, Link Summon Saryuja by using 4 materials, one of which has to be Number 13.

3) Although not shown in this video, if you are still lacking power for Cerberus, place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon. This setup is needed for "Primal Seed", so that we can target "Primal Seed" duo each other to play spells forever and raise the ATK of Cerberus. As long as you don't banish Number 13 with Chaos, everything will be fine.

4) When the ATK of Cerberus is higher than your opponent's LP, revive Number 13 with "Monster Reborn". If there is no space, "Mystik Wok" can help in that regard. Then, overlay into Number 43 by playing "Rank-Up-Magic Launch".

5) Finally, play "Mystik Wok" and target on Cerberus. Don't forget to choose its ATK. With healing to damage conversion via Number 43, you can FTK your opponent.

deck_excerpt: Swarm the field with deadly Harpies!
deck_description:
UNLEASH MAI'S HARPIES!

Harpie Lady is a very underexplored archetype in goat format. Today I'd like to bring my take to the table and will make a detailed primer describing all of my decisions. I hope you enjoy it!

The very first card is Harpie Lady Sisters. Harpie Lady Sisters can be special summoned off Elegant Egotist which is a free special summon. Her stats are decent, being able to beat over 1900 ATK beat sticks as well as having 2100 DEF, being able to also provide a decent defensive wall if needed.

Next we have Harpie Lady 1. She is another standard inclusion that can boost other wind monsters ATK by 300. We include two of her to help fuel the Elegant Egotist special summon as well as boost our bird swarm.

Harpie Lady 2 is our other Harpie inclusion, helping negate flip effect monsters when destroyed by battle. She can searched out by Birdface and Flying Kamakiri if needed.

Silpheed is a great inclusion in any wind deck. His effect to force your opponent to discard a card when destroyed by battle is crazy. If your opponent wants to dodge this effect, they'll be forced to use another card to get him off the field.

Birdface is another staple of Harpie decks, being able to search out any of them when destroyed by battle.

Flying Kamakiri #1 is yet another floater in our deck. It can search out a whole mess of other Wind monsters in the deck. A great target is often Lady Ninja Yae , or Hand of Nephthys .

Lady Ninja Yae is an extremely great card in any Wind deck. Her effect is basically a walking Giant Trunade. If the Sisters are bricking, you can pitch them to activate this effect and summon Silpheed with said discard.

Twin-Headed Behemoth needs no introduction. While it fits in nicely as a Wind type, it's also just an all-around great card to have as a free special summon.

Our Sacred Phoenix can be summoned off of Hand of Nephthys . This card is an exceptional beater that essentially forces your opponent to use a banish effect to get rid of it. 

The other two non-engine cards are Breaker the Magical Warrior and Sangan . These are just no-brainer staples to include in the deck. Next I'm going to get into a few of the spell and traps (I'm only going to discuss the relevant non-staples to save you some reading).

Triangle Ecstasy Spark is a comfortable one-of in the deck that can be used to close out games. If your opponent is low on life points, this will give you a sure-fire method to finish them off.

Harpies' Hunting Ground is another great card in your playbook. Not only does it give you an ATK boost, but can also pop a back row card every time you summon a Harpie. The only thing to keep in mind is that this effect is mandatory, so be careful when you summon your monsters.

 

Finally, we arrive at the last in-engine card: Elegant Egotist. This can be used to special summon a Harpie Lady while you control another one. This card is crazy as it is one of the few in the format that can special summon FROM the deck. 

Every other spell/trap in this deck mostly fall into the staple category, but there are a couple to highlight. Smashing Ground is our card to counter aggro decks - I picked that one over Sakuretsu as we are main decking Royal Decree . Considering Harpies don't utilize any specific traps, I think it fits in very nicely with the deck. It also means we have better odds of using Hunting Ground without having to pop our own back row, since we only run four traps that can set.

The fusion deck consists solely of cheap Wind monsters to act as a bluff as we are never going to use it with this deck.

Finally, I'll cap off this deck with a quick run down of the side deck. We run 1x Spell Canceller as it is Wind type and can be very useful against any spell heavy deck. Kycoo the Ghost Destroyer and Mind Control are both present to counter Chaos. Asura Priest and Tribe-Infecting Virus are present to counter goat control. Lightning Vortex can also be considered a goat counter, but I think it's useful against a variety of monster-heavy decks. 2x Creature Swap make a great fit to side-in if you don't need the Smashing Grounds. It fits in perfectly with this deck, and you can get great results with it in tandem with Birdface or Flying Kamakiri. Poison of the Old Man will give you some extra life points to play with against burn. Considering we already main deck Decree, we don't need to side much for burn. Mirror Force , Ring of Destruction , and Dust Tornado are all present if you decide to swap out Decree for a more traditional backrow setup.

If you made it through all of this, thank you! Drop your own take on this in the comments below.

deck_excerpt: Synchronized Realm FTK ft. Primal Seed
deck_description:
Once upon a time, I made a deck by using Synchronized Realm alongside Linewalker. Now, I have decided to do with "Primal Seed" to show that you can beat up people who are immortal. Yet, the earlier you find Realms, the earlier you can beat the opponent. The mindset is similar to this deck I made but I'll explain anyways.

 

 

Gameplan

1) Since Panda decks are based on lots of Synchro Summons, finding "Synchronized Realm" spells as early as possible will close up the game real quick. Place them whenever you find any. If you have placed all of "Synchronized Realm" spells, whenever you Synchro Summon, you will deal 3 x 500 = 1500 damage in total to your opponent.

2) Although not shown in this video, if your opponent is still alive, place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon to find combo pieces from Banish Zone (BZ) with "Primal Seed" cards.

3) Make sure you have at least two free spaces in Main Monster Zone (MMZ). Then, choose a Synchro Monster to your liking. Now, you have two options...

  • If Synchro Monster is in the GY, revive it with "Monster Reborn". Then, play "De-Synchro" to return it to Extra Deck. Afterwards, revive fitting monsters with "Monster Reborn" and Synchro Summon. If you play "De-Synchro" this time, you can Special Summon said monsters without the need of "Monster Reborn". Rinse and repeat the whole process until your opponent is dead.
  • If Synchro Monster is in the Extra Deck, you can still do the same stuff. If you lack required monsters, simply revive them with "Monster Reborn". If they are on your battlefield, just use them. Don't forget to play "De-Synchro" over and over until you kill your opponent.

4) Choose what to do in #3 and win the game!

Have you ever heard of the famous Trickstar deck of cards? This deck, if you watch the movie, belongs to Skye Zaizen, or the original Aoi Zaizen! In the movie, in addition to the above deck, she also owns an equally powerful deck of cards, which is Marincess. Although she only plays a background role for supporting characters, her cards have left an extremely strong impression on players, especially players who love waifu :v. Here, let's learn about the artwork... oh wrong, learn about these girls and how to build a complete deck of Marincess cards!

Strengths and weaknesses:

Marincess in particular and Cyberse in general are both decks capable of creating good combos. However, compared to some other decks, Marincess has outstanding advantages in the following points.

First, Marincess possesses the ability to overcome opponents' interruptions quite well. If compared to Ignister, if Ignister takes a handtrap, you will be able to pass that turn. However, with Marincess, because your extenders are quite large, you can immediately switch to plans B and C that you have set up. Second, Marincess needs few cards in the Main Deck to operate. Therefore, you can add common cards like Nibiru, handtraps, etc. to block your opponent's path. Third, this strength is similar to Salamangreat, Marincess's ability to recycle resources is extremely good, with tools like Blue Slug, Coral Anenome, Coral Triangle or Marbled Rock.

However, besides that, Marincess has quite fatal weaknesses. That is our boss monster, to be unaffected depends on the survival of the field. If the field is lost, the enhancement will be lost (the increased or unaffected attack will be lost). Although the resource recovery ability is quite good, it burns resources extremely quickly. With each summon to a boss, it takes us nearly half an Extra to reach it. Therefore, Pot of Prosperity, although very powerful, is difficult to use in decks.

Those are the strengths and weaknesses we learned when playing Marincess. Do you know any other strengths and weaknesses? Please share in the comments section below the article!

Main cards:

Marincess Blue Tang

This is considered one of the strongest starters of the Deck. When called to the field, Blue Tang will send you a Marincess monster to the grave. There are quite a few targets for us to send to the grave, for example, Marincess that have the ability to jump from their hand, such as Sea Horse, Springirl, Sleepy Maiden and then add them to their hand thanks to Blue Slug. Or monsters that have good ability to stay in the grave like Mandarin (to spam fields), or Pascalus (recycle traps).

When sending to the Graveyard as a Link Summon material for a WATER monster, you can turn over the first 3 cards of the deck and add 1 Marincess from the deck to your hand. You will often use this card to chain block Link 1 monsters. Specifically: You will use Blue Tang to build Blue Slug (for example), at this time, arrange Blue Slug chain link 1, Blue Tang chain link 2. At that time, Blue Tang will help you avoid handtraps that can target Blue Slug, helping the combo circuit to take place more completely.

It can be said that Blue Tang is an extremely important card, starting the operating system of the entire deck. Playing 3 is out of the question.

Marincess Sea Horse

The second starter of the deck. The ability to jump without chaining is very strong, as long as you only need to own 1 Marincess link monster with an arrow that can only enter 1 Main Monster Zone box. With just 1 Sea Horse, you can create 1 link of 3 easily. (I will tell you the specific combo later!). The second effect is also very good, although rarely used, it sometimes helps you remove weights very well, allowing you to call up 1 WATER from your hand into the box the Marincess link points to. Versatile and convenient, the number of players required is 3.

Marincess Springirl

Springgirl sounds similar to Sea Horse, also has the ability to jump on its own. However, Springirl must have 1 Marincess monster in the grave as a cost. Most of the time in the beginning of the game we don't have many Marincess in the grave, so Springirl will only act as an extender. The second effect also helps us chain block for Link 1 monsters, as well as supports grave feeding to have more room to deploy our other Marincess gameplay.

Should play 2.

Marincess Sleepy Maiden

Like the two monsters above, Sleepy Maiden is also a monster that can jump onto the field by assigning a Marincess card on the field. However, Sleepy Maiden is weaker than Springirl by many points. In addition to not being able to work independently like Springirl, she also has a pretty "big" level: Level 5. That is, if one bad day you can't get to another starter or Marincess Battle Ocean, then oh well: v. Because of Level 5, you cannot use it on Marincess's Link 1 monsters.

To compensate for the above shortcomings of Sleepy Maiden, she can help "attach" a Marincess Link Monster from the grave to another Marincess link. Sleepy Maiden will help Link 4 girls' eff activation go more smoothly. I will tell you specifically later!

Note: When called to the field by eff 1, it will add an ability to the specified card that cannot be destroyed by opp's cards. That is, when leaving the field or being negated (negated) the effect, this ability will also disappear. Please remember to pay attention!

Play 1 (easy to brick).

Marincess Mandarin

Mandarin is also a pretty good extender to extend combos. Of course, Mandarin cannot operate alone (due to its even stricter conditions, having to control 2 or more Marincess on the field). Plus, this is a monster that has a good chance of rising from the grave. Therefore, we don't want to see it much in our hands, but want to put it in the grave to have room to use other extenders. This is possible thanks to Blue Tang and Foolish Burial.

Play 1-2. 1 if you want to cut Mandarin to want other desired cards in your hand.

Marincess Pascalus

Pascalus is a starter, but not a very good starter in the deck. Pascalus does not have the ability to jump on its own, it only works to its maximum effect when you have it and another Marincess except Pascalus in your hand, which only supports creating 1 more body. In addition, Pascalus also has a pretty cool ability. While it is in the grave, except during the sent turn, you can recycle 1 Marincess Spell/Trap in the grave by banishing it. Common targets are Marincess Dive and Marincess Wave - the strongest duo in the deck.

Play 2, because if you hold 3 cards it will become a weight.

The remaining Marincess monsters are not good and are not recommended for use in the Main Deck.

 Marincess Battle Ocean

This is Field Spell, the main card of the deck. Searched by Marincess Sea Angel. The “ocean battlefield” will help greatly strengthen the attack power of our Marincesses. When Link Summoned to the Extra Monster Zone, she will be equipped with up to 3 Link Marincess monsters, thereby enhancing her attack and expanding her hidden abilities. Additionally, when using Crystal Heart as a material, that Marincess will not be affected by the opponent's effects. That means, if opp wants Nibiru now, there is no more chance.

 

Small note: If the field is destroyed, all the ability imposed on Marincess link is no longer there, meaning the unaffected ability as well as the increased attack power also disappears. Please pay attention!

 Play 2, because of the strategy we will rotate around this card.

Marincess Dive

Great addition. Now, Marincess has less difficulty lacking an extender than before. Dive will help you recall a non-linked Marincess from the grave or deck (if there is a Battle Ocean). Not only that, Dive is also searchable by Sea Angel, making the process of setting up your yard easier than ever!

Playing 3 is out of the question.

Marincess Wave

Infinite Impermanences of the deck but much stronger. When you have 1 Marincess link, you have the right to negate the effect of 1 monster on the field. If you control a monster linked to 2 or more Marincess, all of your monsters are immune to card effects. If you control a Link 3 or higher Marincess monster, you are allowed to use it as an active handtrap at any time.

In addition to preventing extremely difficult obstacles from opponents, Wave also helps you protect yourself. A pretty good move is when your opponent controls an effect monster and they cast Nibiru to end you, you can activate Wave. At that time, Nibiru's Tribute is an eff, so your monsters will not be cleared, only the opponent will suffer the consequences. This card is not Once per turn, meaning you can activate as many cards in your hand as you like. This is a pretty good trap card that many decks want to have.

 Note: Like Sky Striker cards, if you cannot negate monster effects, you will not benefit from Wave's effect protection!

Play 2 because of its usefulness.

 Other Spells/Traps are really not useful and should not be used.

Extra Deck:

Marincess Blue Slug

Blue Slug helps you recycle, and is a very effective combo opening card. The common target is Sea Horse, or other extenders to expand combos. Or Blue Tang and Pascalus to prepare for the next turn.

Play 2.

Marincess Sea Angel

We can search Dive, from there if the hand is not too good, we can still end the board with a link 3 monster to play in the next turn.

Play 2.

Marincess Coral Anemone

Coral Anenome will help you drag a monster onto the field to continue spinning. From Coral Anenome, we can easily perform a combo of 1 Link-3 card as follows: Normal 1 any Marincess, link to Sea Angel, click eff to search Marincess Dive. Then click eff Dive to summon the Marincess monster just now. Use the 2 above to Link Summon Coral Anenome. Anenome flashes eff, calling Sea Angel from there to Link-3. But remember, that monster must be called to the zone this card points to. Therefore, if you eat Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit, you will not be able to summon it (because the zone is unknown). You need to pay attention to this!

In addition, Coral Anenome also possesses excellent recycling capabilities. When sent from the field to the grave, you can pick up any 1 Marincess card from the grave. The target for this card is quite diverse, it can be a Wave to continue using, or other combo pieces to continue spinning or the next turn. But this addition is not as important as preserving the field. Therefore, if there is a Battle Ocean field that uses Coral Anenome as a material, if possible, arrange Battle Ocean chain link 1, Coral chain link 2. By doing so, Battle Ocean will be protected from being affected by Ghost Ogre. (And if opp Belle can, Belle has already entered the Coral eff before).

 Because the ability to extend and recycle is extremely good, you should play 2.

Marincess Coral Triangle

Coral Triangle will help you search for Wave, at the cost of sending 1 Water - usually taken from your hand by Coral Anenome - to the grave. Triangle has greatly increased Marincess's speed and mobility. In addition, Coral Triangle also serves as a perfect comeback card. If opp is the only one controlling the monster, you can banish to call Water link monsters with a total Link Rating of 3. Coral Triangle helps you control the battle from 0 very well.

 

Although it is so good, the number of Waves is quite limited, it is not a necessary card for combos. As well as the summon condition being quite difficult (must be Marincess), in the late game when you are almost out of Marincess, this is not a good card.

Therefore, the number of plays will be 1.

Marincess Crystal Heart

There aren't too many highlights. We will mainly use it to link to a Link-4 monster to help that monster become unaffected when there is a Battle Ocean field.

 Play 1.

Marincess Great Bubble Reef

 If in the worst case scenario, you don't have a field and need to deal with a huge boss, what do you do? This is one of the best solutions for you. The ability to add hands on both the opp turn and your own turn is also very interesting, at the cost of banishing 1 WATER from the field or grave, supporting an increase in resources. In addition to the effect of increasing 600 ATK for each banned monster, Great Bubble Reef can defeat high attack and annoying monsters without needing the field. At the same time, it can also help you OTK.

 Play 2. Because, if your monster is banished, you only lose.

Marincess Aqua Argonaut

This is the destination we will aim for in the first turn. Possesses protection effect (prevents opp monsters from punching other monsters while they are in the Extra Monster Zone). Combined with its large ATK and field immunity, this monster is also an extremely difficult opponent to defeat. In addition, Aqua Argonaut possesses two very powerful effects. Aqua Argonaut will help you push away your opponent's obstacles by returning 1 Water on the field. Combined with the negate Spell/Trap effect (on turn opp) by calling a Marincess equipped to this card, Aqua Argonaut is a very difficult obstacle to overcome.

Play 1.


<!-- [if !supportLineBreakNewLine]-->
<!--[endif]-->


 Support cards:

 

Cynet Mining

Searcher for every Cyberse deck, why not play it?

 Play 3.

Called by the Grave/ Crossout Designator

These two cards help you avoid having your combo interrupted. Because Marincess is also a deck that is quite afraid of handtraps.

Splash Mage

Is a mobile Monster Reborn of Cyberse in general and Deck in particular. This will be an important card in the late game so we can maintain the combo.

Play 1.

 

You can play Transcode Talker and Accesscode Talker, but I think the slot for the Extra Deck is quite tight, plus we are almost always restricted to summoning WATER, so I won't use these two cards.

Bahamut Shark + Toadally Awesome

Familiar pair of cards. Because our deck sometimes has the ability to reach 2 levels 4 at the same time, you can use these 2 cards if there are slots left. 

Play 0-1 with each card (If you play 1 Bahamut, you must play 1 Toadally and vice versa).

Number 4: Stealth Kragen

Number 4 is a very good Xyz disruption card, destroying a WATER monster and dealing damage equal to half that monster's ATK. Combined with the effect of converting monsters on the field into WATER, Stealth Kragen can destroy tendons like opponent monsters, preventing opp from setting up on the field. This is a strong monster. Combined with Gozen Match, you can create a rather annoying lock position for opp (can only summon Water monsters).

Maybe consider playing 1.

deck_excerpt: C1 FTK ft. Panda+Arcana Force+Numeron Network
deck_description:
(Disclaimer: Think slow but act quick! One mistake and you can fail, better practice under 300 sec before jumping on Ranked.)

Good day to you! If you are looking at this deck, that means you must have been interested into Numeron decks. Technically speaking, C1 is mostly used as emergency rather than burst, where you can banish all monsters and burst damage is low, if only XYZ s banished were Numerons. What if I told you that burst damage can go high only with your cards, ranging up to 15k, and you can do all in one turn thanks to Panda and Arcana? If you are still curious, keep reading.

 

 

Gameplan

1) Place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon. We will find lots of combo pieces from Banish Zone (BZ) with "Primal Seed" cards, that's why. Also, don't forget to place "Light Barrier" on Field Zone.

2) Revive Arcana either with Saryuja or "Monster Reborn". Pick heads as outcome to always skip your opponent's turn, at the cost of two monsters of yours being sent to GY. Then, revive Accel with "Monster Reborn"...

  • "Light Barrier" guarantees the outcome of Arcana without coin flip but you don't have to use Barrier, since you can kill Arcana with "Offerings to the Doomed" to reset and try again with "Monster Reborn". It's irrelevant until the big setup is ready but Barrier saves you a lot of time for hitting the right outcome.

3) XYZ Summon Number 62 and then overlay into C62, all thanks to using Arcana + Accel as materials. Then, destroy it with Offerings...

  • This setup is the easiest XYZ Summon you could ever possibly do, which can be also considered as highest potential burst later on. If you don't have C62, you can replace it with "Galaxy-Eyes Full Armor Photon Dragon" to overlay with Number 62. You can check it in "Side Deck".
  • If you don't have any of these XYZ cards, replace them with "Galaxy-Eyes Cipher Dragon", seen in "Side Deck". Rather than spending UR, you can spend gems to buy "Rage of Cipher" structure deck to have at least two of them.

4) Revive Accel + Arcana with "Monster Reborn" and XYZ Summon Number 97 by using them as materials. Destroy Number 97 with Offerings and XYZ Summon Number 97 one more time with same monsters...

  • Although not used in this deck, if you wish to increase burst damage further, Number 22 is the highest one as Level 8 DARK XYZ monster, seen in "Side Deck". However, there is a catch: You have to use Level 8 DARK monsters as materials. So, you have to place "Lair of Darkness" to change attribute of all monsters into DARK to XYZ Summon Number 22 later on. Otherwise, Number 97 is the cheapest (R) to craft and carry through on your plan.

5) With big XYZ monsters in your GY, it's time to send Chaos Emperor to the same area. If you have "Offerings to the Doomed" and "Monster Reincarnation" in your hand, destroy Chaos Emperor with Offerings and return it to your hand with Reincarnation. Then, banish 1 LIGHT XYZ and 1 DARK XYZ to Special Summon Chaos Emperor. Repeat the same process but not before you have Offerings + Reincarnation in your hand, which can be found with "Primal Seed" cards.

6) Revive 3 x Level 1 monsters with "Monster Reborn" and XYZ Summon Number 1 by using these little dudes as materials. Then, repeat #5 one more time to not banish Chaos Emperor by accident and have him ready in your hand.

7) Overlay into C1 with Number 1. Then, Special Summon Chaos Emperor by banishing Number 1 and any DARK monster. This time, revive Arcana with "Monster Reborn" when "Light Barrier" is present. As explained in #2, choose the outcome as heads. If you don't want to use "Light Barrier", good luck hitting heads because if you don't, get ready for searching Offering + Monster Reborn with "Primal Seed" cards.

8) With turn skip trick ready, don't forget to have at least two more monsters on your side for Arcana to send them to GY. After placing "Numeron Network" on the field, you can end your turn and skip your opponent's one by sending two monsters you control but Arcana to GY...

  • Also, to not miss out anything, change the button on the lower right corner of the screen to either "ON" or "Auto". It can be changed within settings under "Duel", where you can change "Activation Confirmation" to "Switch + Hold" for manual setup.

9) It's your turn now. Activate C1 to bring forth and deal 15000 damage in total for the FTK. Rather than banishing XYZ monsters on the field, banishing XYZ monsters from GY via Chaos Emperor also works for C1.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Monster Reborn" is given for free, if you have played the tutorial to save 30 UR!

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Into The Void" + "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Primal Seed" + "Pot of Acquistiveness" + "Ravenous" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 60 SR and 60 UR!

- "Number C1" + "Numeron Network" can be found within "Number Recall" Secret Pack to save 30 SR and 30 UR!

- "Formula Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- As of this writing, "Number 62" and "Number C62" can be found within timed pack called "Galactic Evolution" to save 60 UR! Don't miss them out before it's too late. However, once they are gone, you can instead find "Number 62" and "Galaxy-Eyes Full Armor Photon Dragon" within "Nebula Cyclone" Secret Pack to carry on with the same plan, still costing 60 UR!

- "Arcana Force" + "Light Barrier" can be found within "Hand of Fate" Secret Pack to save 30 SR and 30 UR! If you wish, you can cut "Light Barrier" but be mindful of consequences explained in the guide. Consequently, you can also cut 3 x "Chicken Game" to save 90 UR as well because Ancient won't have anything to tutor by removing four field spells.

 

So, in total, you can save up to 540 SR and 330 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems and/or want to remove some cards. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. If you have any questions, feel free to ask. Have fun in Master Duel!

Category: Tournament Meta Decks (TCG)

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Jordi Wang

Tournament: Barcelona WCQ Regional – October 12th 2023

Placement: 1st Place

Hey! In this deck, we will FTK our opponent with "Number 43" thanks to "Number 100" but not with well-known setup. Instead of Utopiforce where damage output is limited, we will turn our thinking around to deal as high as 255k damage! Yes, you heard me right, so why don't you take a look?

 

 

Gameplan

1) At one point, discard at least one of Coltwings with Ravenous but try to aim discarding both, if you can.

2) Place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon. This is needed to find combo pieces from Banish Zone (BZ) with "Primal Seed" cards. Also, place Xiangsheng, which will play in an important role later on.

3) Before you do anything, clear everything on Main Monster Zones (MMZ) but Chaos Emperor with "Offerings to the Doomed". Then, Special Summon both Coltwings with the help of Saryuja and "Monster Reborn". By reviving both Coltwings, you will fill last remaining spots with two tokens.

4) The current level of Coltwing is based on the sum of level of tokens and original level of Coltwing. This is addition, which is actually done only by tokens, not setting its level to fixed amount. Therefore, by playing "Galaxy Queen's Light" on Coltwing, its level will increase with respect to level of tokens. Reason is that you will also increase the level of tokens. Here is the process:

  • At first, the level of Coltwing will be level 10 >>> Coltwing (4) + Token (3) + Token (3)
  • Galaxy Queen's Light >>> Target Coltwing (level 10) >>> Tokens will be level 10
  • New calculation = Token (10) + Token (10) + Coltwing (4) = Coltwing (24)

5) Repeat the step explained in #4, by targeting only on Coltwing and nothing else.

6) When you think it's enough, clear tokens with Offerings. You can also clear Saryuja and Coltwings afterwards for more space, if you wish.

7) XYZ Summon both "Number 13" monsters with Level 1 monsters. Then, XYZ Summon "Number 100" because you fit the criteria.

8) So, you have "Number 100" and high level Chaos. Activate Xiangsheng to raise the rank of "Number 100" up to the level of Chaos by targeting both.

9) Activate the ability of "Number 100" by detaching one of Number 13 monsters to increase its ATK. Since you have a XYZ monster with high amount of Rank, the ATK of Number 13 will be naturally higher than your opponent's LP.

10) Revive Number 13 with "Monster Reborn". Then, overlay into Number 43 with "Rank-Up-Magic Launch".

11) Play "Mystik Wok" and target on "Number 100". Choose its ATK to convert healing into damage with Number 43 for the FTK.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Monster Reborn" is given for free, if you have completed the tutorial to save 30 UR!

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contact Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Number 100: Numeron Dragon" can be found within "Number Recall" Secret Pack to save 30 UR! Also, as of this writing, you can try finding it from "Galactic Evolution" timed pack.

- "Pot of Acquisitiveness" + "Primal Seed" + "Ravenous" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 60 SR and 60 UR!

- "Into The Void" + "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Formula Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 480 SR and 150 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. Let me know if you have any questions and have fun in Master Duel!

deck_excerpt: Blue-Eyes and Dogmatika makes Tyrant Trap Loop EZ
deck_description: Clear the board and defeat your Enemy with Blue-Eyes White Dragon!

Have you ever read about Norse mythology? Do you like card genres that contain action role-playing games (RPGs)? If you are interested in the above 2 things, then congratulations, Runick was created by Konami to serve your needs. Released in Deck Build Pack: Tactical Masters, Runick became an extremely powerful card clan, because it contained the same ability as the previous Sky Striker. So what are the elements that constitute this power? Let's find out!

The Runick deck has a mechanic quite similar to Sky Striker, as the main heavy weapons of both these decks are powerful Spell cards. Unlike Sky Striker, Runick doesn't have a Monster in the Main Deck, but in return, each of Runick's Spell cards has effects that affect the opponent's deck when executed.

Runick's Quick-Play Spell cards allow you to choose only 1 of 2 effects, but only on condition that you skip the next Battle Phase, and only use it once a turn.

One is that you will use a unique effect of each card and then expel a number of opponent cards.

Second, you will call 1 Runick beast from the Extra Deck to the field.

Each Runick monster from this Extra Deck is not very powerful, but will have quite good effects to support your tactics, so consider which effect to use in specific circumstances!

Main cards:

Runick Tip

The most powerful Searcher deck, helps you find the necessary piece to play so why not play 3?

Play 3 with every build involving Runick.

Runick Flashing Fire

Flashing Fire has almost the same mission as Afterburner, but can only shoot special summoned monsters, in return it can banish the first 2 cards of the opponent deck. Think Flashing Fire is as dead at turn 1 as Afterburner? That's okay, you can use it to call out Fusion monsters, combined with the Runick Fountain environment card to continue playing.

Play 3.

Runick Destruction

A very powerful Spell/Trap destroyer card! After canceling, there are 4 more cards on top of the opponent's deck, if we calculate it again and again, we will gain a lot, not 1-for-1 like Mystical Space Typhoon. And if we accidentally pick up this card turn 1, we can also use it to call out the Fusion beast. A very good card, worth playing in the Deck.

Play 3.

Runick Freezing Curses

The negate effect is very strong, almost like Widow Anchor. Freezing Curses allow banish the opponent's first 3 cards as well. Just removing 1 obstacle, banish 3 top, a pretty high number for the number of cards banish by 1 effect of Runick, why not play?

Play 3.

Runick Slumber

The protection effect reminds us of a card that is almost the same, which is the Eagle Booster. But stronger than Eagle Booster in that Slumber can protect monsters even while you control monsters in the Main Monster Zone, plus can lightly "protect" opponents, so that they do not deduct all your origin points. From there, Slumber can assist you in resetting the battle in the next turn, in addition to banish the first 3 cards of the opponent's deck, causing quite a lot of discomfort. However, in the deck mix, this protection effect is quite redundant, because we will almost have insurance in a different gameplay.

Play 2

Runick Golden Droplet

The effect is quite interesting, the banish is quite chatty, but the opponent is the one who gets the plus. Most of the time we will use eff to call Runick from the Extra Deck in the early stages of the game, at the end of the game if you feel you can get out of your opponent's deck, the Golden Droplet is a very good card to create victory for you.

Play 1

Runick Smiting Storm

Effect 1 is a little better for the Golden Droplet. Based on the number of cards on your opponent's court, you banish the card on top of their deck. Quite good in the last turns, but the first ones are not too good. Therefore, we will play 1-2.

Runick Dispelling

The Dispelling effect is quite passive, having to wait for the opponent to pick up the hand before being allowed to activate to jerk the hand and banish 2 top. Not too tasty because it is not actively activated, almost only using effect 2 is the main one, so it should only be played 0-1.

Runick Fountain

The Fountain effect is very strong, supporting you to make it difficult for your opponent. It is possible to turn all Runick Quick-Play Spell leaves into handtraps, which is quite detrimental to them. Combined with a very strong recycling effect, we can immediately activate the cards we have just drawn by Fountain to continue to annoy them in turning. What's better?

Play max, should play 1 more Terraforming to search this card easier.

Runick Allure

Allure will help us resource opponent Deck faster. However, this is not a very important piece, and can be searched by a Fusion beast, so the number of plays only needs to be 0-1.

The Extra Deck:

Most of the time we won't call the Runick Fusion beasts "properly", but rather through the Quick-Play Spells we talked about above. Fusion monsters will assist you in deploying tactics more easily.

Hugin the Runick Wings

Hugin will help you get your hands on Fountain, helping you deploy long-term tactics more quickly. In addition, Hugin will tell you to avoid 1 Harpie's Feather Duster, avoid losing your Field Spell or important cards, even when Hugin first calls. For example, when an opponent clicks Harpie's Feather Duster, I activate the Runick Quick-Play Spell in Chain Link 2 to call out Hugin. Later, Hugin himself banish it to combat the cancelled Fountain.

Play 3.

Munin the Runick Wings

Almost like Hugin, Munin will help you find Runick Allure. Allure isn't so important that Munin's value is less than Hugin's, but Munin also has the ability to protect your Runick, especially Field Spell, against target 1 bit (by negate that effect). The 1000 LP plus effect helps you live longer, sometimes helping you win in a gunfight.

Play 1.

Geri the Runick Fangs

Geri will help you restore Fountain or Allure in the grave, supporting you to continue the gameplay. Besides, Geri can die with a leaf on the field if it is destroyed through combat, and cannot be destroyed through effects, helping you fish a little more to survive.

Play 2.

Freki the Runick Fangs

In my opinion, I don't appreciate Freki very much. The first effect must have an attack on this card for you to be allowed to banish the first 2 cards of the opponent deck. With Deck Runick, you can barely punch (because you almost lost the Battle Phase), and your opponent will not be foolish to punch this one. The second effect, I judge is also a bit redundant. Since your Runick Quick-Play Spell is always best recycled by Fountain, there may be no need to play this one. If you want to play, you can consider playing 1-2, if you have excess slots, you can play 3.

Other cards:

This is a rare deck that does not require the use of monsters, so there are several options offered to interfere with the opponent:

– Spells that limit opponent actions: Dimensional Fissure, Messenger of Peace,...

– Trap genres limit action, hinder opponent action such as: There Can Be Only One, Gozen Match, Rivalry of Warlords ,... (do not recommend playing Macro Cosmos because it will "kick" with my Spell)

– Cards enhance the ability to draw cards and get the necessary pieces: Card of Demise, Pot of Duality,..

(It is especially recommended to play Card of Demise because this card has the ability to add up a lot).

And there are many other options, you can find out for yourself.

Observe:

Since Runick is pure deck control, if you can go ahead, your win rate is also very high. If you successfully prepare strong floodgate cards, you will slow down the rematch. Relying slowly but surely, Runick would then take the initiative, gaining the upper hand throughout the match.

However, Runick has the same weaknesses as other Spell/Trap control decks. If the floodgates you have are not strong enough to completely hinder the opponent, you will easily lose resources and lead to loss. And also because this is a control deck, it is easy to be hindered by cards like Topologic Trisbaena or Topologic Zeroboros, when these 2 cards can sweep the yard we have prepared.

Runick is a deck that uses many spells, so it is easy to be overcome by cards capable of countering, against me using Spells such as Anti-Spell Fragrance, Secret Village of the Spellcaster,... So in tournaments where many people use these 2 cards, your chances of winning will also be low.

That's how I feel about Runick. What else do you guys feel? If so, please leave it in the comments section to let everyone know more!

deck_excerpt: Seventh Emperors FTK ft. The Dark Magicians+Magical Contract Door
deck_description:
(Disclaimer: For this deck to work, you have to act calm but play quick. I suggest you practicing under 300 sec rule before moving onto Ranked. Otherwise, it's fine to play on Casual with 480 sec.)

Greetings! In this deck, we will FTK our opponent with "Rebirth of Seventh Emperors" while trying to repeat as many times as we can with "The Dark Magicians" + "De-Fusion" combination alongside giving our opponent extra cards with "Gold Moon Coin" + "Magical Contract Door" to increase burn potential. Let me show you.

 

 

Gameplan

1) Throughout the game, XYZ Summon "Djinn" by using 2 x Cthugua as materials. Then, overlay into "C39" with "Limited Barian's Force". Also, don't forget to XYZ Summon "Number 39" with 2 x Level 1 monsters as materials.

2) Link Summon Saryuja by using 4 materials, one of which has to be C39 and shouldn't be Number 39 at all.

3) Place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon. Banish targets has to be Djinn + C39 no matter what. Also, with ME-PSY-YA + Chaos Emperor present, you can find combo pieces from Banish Zone (BZ) with "Primal Seed" cards no problem.

4) Try depleting your Main Deck by playing "Into the Void" + "Allure of Darkness". If you must, don't forget to fetch banished DARK monsters with "Primal Seed".

5) Play "Polymerization" to bring forth "The Dark Magicians" by using "Fusion Parasite" + Spellcaster as materials. Then, play "The Humble Sentry" to reshuffle Seventh Emperors and activate "The Dark Magicians" to draw Seventh Emperors to play it later on.

6) Activate Seventh Emperors. Number 39 will be automatically tributed. Remember banished XYZ monsters by Chaos Emperor? Now, you can Special Summon one of them and it has to be Djinn. Later on, it will be C39. In short, while picking targets, pick opposite attributed monster of what was present before. LIGHT >>> DARK >>> LIGHT >>> DARK etc.

7) In order to play Seventh Emperors again, we have to reset "The Dark Magicians" and do the trick explained in #5. Just play "De-Fusion" and bring out materials to reuse them again with "Fusion Parasite".

8) When there is nothing to pick with Seventh Emperors, that means it's time to banish with Chaos Emperor for another time. If you have done everything right, C39 should be the one present on the battlefield. After you have placed your first Chaos Emperor on top of your deck with "Back to Square One", you can banish other XYZ monsters with second Chaos Emperor, which are Djinn + Number 39.

9) Fetch the first Chaos Emperor with "Magical Contract Door" to empty your Main Deck, again. As long as you give a spell other than combo pieces, you will be fine. This step is where you can enlarge your opponent's hand besides "Gold Moon Coin" and it can be repeated, provided that you have reshuffled the first Chaos Emperor with "The Humble Sentry".

10) Repeat the whole process from #5 to #9 until you had it enough. To sum up...

  • Use "The Dark Magicians" alongside "The Humble Sentry" to activate "Seventh Emperors" later on. Pick opposite attributed target of what was tributed before. Reset with "De-Fusion" afterwards.
  • When there is nothing to banish, shuffle Chaos Emperor with "Back to Square One" and rebanish other XYZ s with different Chaos Emperor. Then, fetch it with "Magical Contract Door" and give your opponent a spell as a gift.

11) Before you end your turn, change the button on the lower right corner of the screen to either "ON" or "Auto". It can be changed within settings under "Duel", where you can change "Activation Confirmation" to "Switch + Hold" for manual setup. After you have ended your turn, confirm "Into the Void" first to not take any damage from "Seventh Emperors". Then, click all "Seventh Emperors" for the FTK.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "The Dark Magicians" can be collected by purchasing "Vortex of Magic" deck. 30 UR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Into The Void" + "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Primal Seed" + "Pot of Acquistiveness" + "Fusion Parasite" + "Magical Contract Door" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 90 SR and 60 UR!

- "Formula Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 510 SR and 120 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems and/or want to remove some cards. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. If you have any questions, feel free to ask. Have fun in Master Duel!

Tactic: Labrynth – Mischievous Demons!

Have you heard of beasts with the Fiend system – the Evil system? This is a famous card system with many hideous beasts with many monstrous shapes. But now, these notions have been almost completely eliminated by a card that appears in the Deck Build Pack: Tactical Masters (in TCG, Tactical Masters), which is Labrynth. This card clan not only possesses a rather good-looking appearance but is also very powerful. Namely, What is the above deck power? Let's find out!

Main cards:

Arianna the Labrynth Servant

Arianna is a rather all-powerful maid of Labrynth. Deck's Searcher, which helps you find any piece of Labrynth name except itself. In addition, although less used, you can draw 1 card if a monster leaves the field by Normal Trap and specially summon 1 Fiend/ Set 1 Spell or Trap from your hand. Arianna is an extremely effective and indispensable piece of the puzzle in Labrynth.

Note: You can only use 1 of 2 effects: Search or Draw in the same turn!

Playing 3 is a no-brainer.

Lovely Labrynth of the Silver Castle

This is a Level 8 beast that doesn't know how to jump on its own, so what kind of field can trigger the effect? Don't worry because we'll be calling up Lovely with Labrynth's Trap cards that we'll tell about in the background. The ability to shoot cards and recycle is very strong, especially with the deck controlling the match with Trap. But this beast has a pretty bad level (Level 8), so if you pick it up, you only have coals because of this dumbbell.

Have to play 2, because if you play 1, this card is banished, will lose.

Lady Labrynth of the Silver Castle

Debuting in Darkwing Blast, Lady Labrynth greatly increased Labrynth's speed. The summon conditions are simple, just have a Labrynth card or Normal Trap activated during that turn to get on the field. Besides, when there is a Normal Trap activated, you have the right to Set 1 Normal Trap with another name with it from the Deck. Our deck has many Normal Traps that can be used in many different situations, such as Dimensional Barrier to lock summon, or Infinite Impermanence to negate the opponent's monster effect,... In addition, when there is a set card, Lady Labrynth cannot be targeted as well as destroyed by the opponent effect, so the opponent will have a hard time if you want to prevent Lady Labrynth from giving you an advantage.

Usually, when you or your opponent clicks the trap, arrange the Lady Labrynth to activate first and then you should activate the effect of the card you want. By doing so, you will gain more advantages than immediately activating that card.

Play 2-3.

Labrynth Chandraglier

Chandraglier and Stovie Torbie have in common that they can search the Labrynth Trap, at the cost of itself and 1 leaf from the hand. In addition, it is possible to restore itself when a monster leaves the field by Normal Trap. However, the number of Labrynth Spell/Trap is not much in the deck, as well as these 2 cards when activated are deducted, so the number does not need to be too much.

Play 0-2 with each card (reasons for playing 2 will be mentioned later).

Cooclock allows you to click right in the turn that has just been set down but must control 1 Labrynth monster. Since the number of Labrynth monsters to open in the deck is quite small, Cooclock should not play much in the deck.

Play 0-1.

Labrynth Labyrinth

Labrynth Labyrinth is Field Spell, which also assists for shooting cards on the field like Conquistador the Golden Land. However, Labyrinth is only effective when accompanied by Welcome Labrynth, for which we do not have too many Welcome in the deck. Therefore, the number that should be played is 1.

Welcome Labrynth

The card assists you in pulling the necessary pieces of Labrynth from the deck onto the court. Although we are limited to only calling Fiend from Deck or Extra Deck until the end of the next turn, but most of us only call Fiend beasts so it does not affect. Also, when a monster is left by a Normal Trap, you can turn this card back from the grave. 2 The ability to pull from the deck and recycle itself is very good, making the deck able to play for a long time to continue to pressure the opponent.

Play 3.

Big Welcome Labrynth

Debuting in Photon Hypernova, Big Welcome Labrynth is like a new revolution for Labrynth, with 2 very powerful effects and fit into the whole song. If in the past, you would hardly benefit if you wanted to use the effects when a beast left Labrynth's yard, it has been different since this leaf came out. Being able to exchange 1 monster on his field with a Labrynth beast, Big Welcome has made it easier than ever to trigger effects when a monster leaves the Labrynth's yard.

 In addition, Big Welcome also allows "pedaling" 1 card on the opponent's field to hand if there is 1 Fiend monster level 8, or 1 Fiend monster on his field. Usually, we will use the effect when there are Fiend Level 8 monsters to remove more obstacles to the opponent, so that from there, we will deploy the gameplay as well as have more time to prepare.

Play 3.

The rest of Labrynth's cards are not very effective and are also of little use.

II. Supporting cards included:

Absolute King Back Jack

If you play the duo of Chandraglier and Stovie Torbie, you should play this card. The Absolute King Back Jack will serve as bait to bid for Chandraglier/Stovie Torbie, or simply to Normal Summon and use it to Link Summon. Then Jack will show you and turn the opponent to set 1 more card from the top of the deck to surprise them. A card that works very well.

 Play 0 if you play very little copy the above 2 variations, play 3 if you play a lot.

Temple of the Kings

Temple of the Kings helps you immediately deploy gameplay right in the first turn, making the speed of game control faster. The only weakness is that this is the Hard Once per turn effect (it can only be used of all cards with the same name once in a turn). Therefore, if you draw these 2 cards in the first turns, it is quite deadly.

 Play 1-2.

In addition to the above cards, we will need to play more Normal Trap cards to hinder the opponent, as well as to support the execution of our tactics such as:

Compulsory Evacuation Device

The trap card is old, but it is never outdated. Most cases assist you in removing obstacles that your opponent has worked hard to build; but at the same time, Compulsory Evacuation Device also helps you rescue in time in the most ironic circumstances.

Dogmatika Punishment

The famous bombardment card of Dogmatika. If you play this card, you should play cards that bombard or obstruct opponents when sent from the Extra Deck to the grave such as Elder Entity N'tss, Wind Pegasus @Ignister,...

Archfiend’s Ghastly Glitch

The ability to bombard when there are Fiend monsters on the field is very suitable for the gameplay of this deck.

Weight Measuring

Trap cards help eliminate rival monsters without targeting nor destroying.

Besides, there are the following cards that should also be considered:

Eradicator Epidemic Virus

Deck Devastation Virus

Ice Dragon’s Prison

Dimensional Barrier

Evenly Matched

…

And there are some other strong Normal Traps to consider.

Continuous Trap cards

We can play annoying and famous Trap cards, which hinder opponents such as:

Skill Drain

Gozen Match

Rivalry of Warlords

…

The above trap cards you can play and change depending on the format and place/tournament you play regularly.


Reviews: Tactical Labrynth – Mischievous Demons!

 Since Labrynth is a control deck, if you get ahead, your odds of winning are also very high. If you go ahead, prepare a full line, the deck will start to work. From turn 3 onwards, when things go well, Labrynth will start showing off his very scary grind game abilities.

 The biggest weakness is probably the early stages of the game. Our key cards, Welcome Labrynth or Big Welcome Labrynth are easily blocked by handtraps. The field is not more than enough money to block the opponent, so we need to play floodgates to stop the opponent's advance. But the selection and use of floodgates also needs to be reasonably considered so as not to "squeeze" yourself.

 That's how I feel when I play Labrynth. What else do you have to share or feel? Please leave below the comment section for everyone to know!

deck_excerpt: Angel of Mischief FTK ft. Spirit Converter+Harmonic Waves+Maple Maiden
deck_description:
Good day to you! Are you up to learn a trick or two? After finding out about "Spirit Converter" alongside recently released card called "Maple Maiden" in Master Duel, I decided to win a game with my beloved Mischief. If combined with "Harmonic Waves", you can attach everything to Mischief and nothing can stand in your way!

 

 

Gameplan

1) At one point, XYZ Summon Dullahan with 2 x Level 1 monsters as materials and overlay into Mischief...

  • For the sake of budget, you can cut Dullahan and start with Mischief instead because it's not that hard to bring forth Level 4 monsters with either Saryuja or "Monster Reborn".

2) Place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon to find combo pieces from Banish Zone (BZ) with "Primal Seed" cards.

3) To win with Angel of Mischief, she has to have 10 materials with her. To attach materials, you have to utilize "Spirit Converter" but how...

  • "Spirit Converter" isn't hard once per turn. It means that you can destroy it with MST to reset its ability and use it again.
  • The attached monster has to be Level 4 LIGHT one. Fortunately, you can adjust both level and attribute of any monster you wish:
    • "Harmonic Waves" can set the level of monster to 4.
    • "Maple Maiden" can change the attribute of every monster on the field, much like "DNA Transplant" seen in Side Deck.
    • Don't forget to use "Monster Reborn" and utilize said cards accordingly on revived monster to your preference.
    • Although not mandatory, if you have monsters in your hand, you can play "Contract with the Void" to send them to GY for more resources for "Monster Reborn" but don't send "Primal Seed" to BZ by accident.

4) Congratulations, you win the duel!

 

What a lovely finish! I would love to save up some SR and UR points, how about you? If so, keep reading:

deck_excerpt: I've won, thanks to the idea of "Focus on winning"... And I'll keep my eyes on winning, JUST LIKE HOW YOU ALL WANTED!!
deck_description:
I've designed quite a few decks that can attempt to use Z-ARC in some capacity and thanks to the cards introduced in AGOV, you only technically need to run Gate Magician and Soul of the Supreme Celestial King in the Main Deck if you want to include it. That said, since it's still Pendulum and additionally it's an anime protagonist's deck, it has plenty of cards to support finding those same pieces and expanding on them further without the need of relying on cards outside of the engine. So, enhancing the PendMa engine further (though I consider this to be horizontal in terms of overall power and not necessarily better than it), witness, Z-ARC!


- Difficulty -
★★★★☆
Despite this being a midrange deck, your 4k/4k boss monster doesn't actually do anything. The original Z-ARC is banned at the time of writing this but a 4k/4k that can continually summon itself and gain protections whilst enhancing the effects of our cards isn't awful. It just makes it so that we don't have to play protect the castle at all. We can just focus on winning the game and navigating the board. Due to the fact that the wincon doesn't do much besides be a large body then, most of the difficulty comes from it being a pendulum deck and needing to make decisions between whether or not certain cards are better as scales or as summons that turn. Lastly, you'll need to have a Supreme King Gate occupying the Pend Zone sometimes or dual Magician Scales at others to proc some of the most impactful effects in this deck. Don't you just love Pendulum in Highlander?

 - Consistency -
★★★☆☆
Most hands you should setup a Pendulum Magician play or Z-ARC; however, it's worth pointing out that since we're not on Joker our consistency is decreased by a small margin when it comes to specifically utitlizing the Odd-Eyes cards by themselves. If you were to update the strategy, I would strongly recommend paying the 1p for Performapal Skullcrobat Joker and either dropping a Duelist Alliance or going up to 50.

- Sackiness -
★☆☆☆☆
Pendulum Call is the only real luck sacking card here. Everything else we do is literally setup. Though, we're technically on 3 copies of Pendulum Call and one way to loop it from the GY so... eh. If original Z-ARC wasn't banned this deck would sack quite a bit through resummoning it over and over.

- Viability -
★★☆☆☆
I don't think in a truly competitive environment Pendulum could ever be terribly viable, especially with the open decklists now; however, the list can take wins against complacent opponents. Furthermore, Pendulum Call and Sky Iris will protect our scales and the non-Magician engines don't actually need to Pendulum Summon at all to be effective, they just need to be on field.

Your standard play with Darkwurm/Gate Magician will just exactly copy the TCG counterpart. Scale Gate Magician and then scale Gate Zero. When you Pendulum Summon, search the Trap. Alternatively, if you already opened Gate Magician, then just scale a Gate. Use Gate Magician's effect in hand by sending Dark Rebellion Xyz Dragon to the GY and summon it for essentially free then search the Trap. The Fusion Materials for the traps include the Pendulum Magicians whose names are always treated as those cards so you can deck thin and/or have alternatives if you value the Main Deck targets more than the Extra Deck targets or vice versa. And yes, Supreme King Gate Magician is a "Supreme King," "Supreme King Gate," and a "Magician" Pendulum Monster. The Trap allows us to summon Odd-Eyes Arcray Dragon who is our stand-in for Z-ARC. As its name is always treated as Z-ARC, we can use it for all relevant effects but due to this as well, it means we can play it as an Unbound card under the Trinity ruleset.

My Pendulum decks usually aim to be flashy but as we're playing a midrange deck with very minimal Normal Monsters, the flashiest plays we can do are regulated to the following:

  • Performapal Odd-Eyes Dissolver: Bait the last attack, prevent the destruction, the have 2 monsters towards Exceed the Pendulum or start your turn with a Fusion Summon of Starving Venom Fusion Dragon.
  • Supreme King Dragon Lightwurm: Chronograph Sorcerer, Exceed the Pendulum, Supreme King Dragon Odd-Eyes, and Wings of Light (with Z-ARC on Field) all can enable Lightwurm to quick-synchro into cards like Supreme King Dragon Clear Wing and Supreme King Dragon Dark Rebellion. Or just go into our full roster of Synchro 8s on our own turn.

Since the engines are virtually independent and don't rely on much to get going, you can technically get away with running more standard interaction than you might be used to running with a Pendulum deck, just be mindful that your ceiling and protections aren't the greatest depending on circumstances you either make for yourself or are just simply unlucky enough to draw into.

45 Card Deck = 3 Points with 3p used.
1p Supreme King Gate Magician (Extra Copy)
1p Duelist Alliance (Extra Copy)
.5p Pendulum Call
.5p Draco Berserker of the Tenyi

Have fun. This engine is honestly really neat and Exceed the Pendulum while being one of the cooler Pendulum Link cards in history, has like... so few practical applications that it makes me excited to see what on-summon Pendulum Monsters we'll be getting in the future.
