deck_excerpt: Local/Regional ready list for Infernoble Knights Post AGOV
deck_description:
With Kashtira out of the way, Infernoble may finally be ready to blaze into the Metagame as a resiliant combo deck with a strong resource loop and the ability to play very well in simplified gamestates. With the Legacy support from DUNE and the new tools afforded to us by Angelica's Angelic Ring in AGOV, we can largely say goodbye to Shifter, and hope for greener pastures.

 

Whats new? 

- Angelica's Angelic Ring

Ring is finally here, and gives us a truely worthwhile piece of equipment to grab from grave with Charles' Endphase effect, this protects our board from some of the metagame's most potent boardbreaking spells in DRNM and Superpoly, by negating thier effects at point of resolution. This makes our main endboard significantly more difficult to break.

-Ra'Ten, The Heavenly General

Ra'ten alone is a nice piece of extra interaction that we can pick up to go second with, allowing for an extra pop as we enter the battle phase, however, where this card really shines is in games two and three, were we can side into Great Shogun Shien and Eka, the Flame Buddy for matchups like Runick variants, Purrely, and other spell heavy decks, as ending on ra'ten is the key to geting this combo online. It is extremely consistent, with minimal settup and allows us to potentially end the game before the oponent hits their first draw phase.

-Other new tools I've forgone for this list

S.P Little Night - without a doubt should be in this list, likely replaceing Ferocious Flame Swordsman, I've chosen to exclude it due to its prohibitively expensive pricetag, currently sitting comfy at $80

Diabelstar, the Black Witch and accompanying engine - The package of 2-3 wanted, 1 Diabelstar, and 1 Luciela is undoubtedly a great piece of the engine, as acessing a lvl 7 body can be great with otherwise bricky hands for turning ash into a Baronne, however, again due to the price of WANTED being 50 a piece and Diabelstar herself at almost 30, the engine is just prohibitively expenisive compared to the arguably better engine of Kash, which nets a potent, hand neutral distruption, and the potential to make zeus extremely easy off of any normal summonable four plus riseheart.

Matchups and closing notes -

Due to extraneous issues, I have not had the time to extensively test into the current Meta decks, including Unchained, Purrely, Labrynth, and Rescue Ace.

Some other potential inclusions include bystials in the sideboard, as they allow a normal summoned Oliver to make baronne, and are strong into Lab and Tearlament

In closing, I believe Infernoble can carve out its spot in the meta as a new contender similar, but less powerful than full power superheavy samurai from this past summer, as a deck that combos to high heaven and ends on piles of interactions.

Hope anyone who desides to go with my list does well with it.
Fear the ancient birds
You can add some Kashtira cards if you want additional level/rank 7 synergy.

deck_excerpt: Bless the name of Rilliona and- for the love of Ninaruru, would someone clear the backlog for the guild already?!
deck_description:
My version of adjustments to the Witchcrafter Starter for Trinity Format.

As referenced in the original starter, the Witchcrafter archetype allows us to make pretty generously potent plays with just our Normal Summon or any one of the lower level Witchcrafters (whom I will refer to as Apprectices for the purposes of this guide). Due to this, we can play very nicely with a coalition of other Spellcasters and related support to eek out advantage engines outside of just what the normal deck would provide. We'll be taking advantage of Windwitch Monsters, Spellbook Spells, Odd-Eyes, and more of the Possessed Engine to try and snowball hard.


- Difficulty -
★★☆☆☆
Witchcrafter are a very unga bunga strategy with all of the ceiling in Trinity being limited to applications of Golem Aruru, Witchcrafter Masterpiece, and determining if you'll be using the Spell for its effect or for Discard fodder. That's about it. Since that's the core of our strategy, to supplement it we're going to reduce the floor even further with our various 1 card combos and safe lines of play to back us up.

 - Consistency -
★★★★☆
This strategy is rather consistent as basically any Apprentice + Spell enables Haine with varying degrees of annoyances attached. Since this isn't a purist deck; however, you may be a bit pressed to find interaction outside of Haine and Aruru as we want the majority of our good cards to be Spells that can double as Discard fodder, so, our Traps aren't exactly premium, nor guaranteed to be cycled into (barring Spellbook Tower gamestates).

- Sackiness -
★★★☆☆
You can run Heavy Storm in this deck in place of Last Will if you'd like to add another sack factor to the deck. Your Cont. Spell/Traps should benefit from the nuke either way in the long term. Regardless, we can't sack very well outside of cards like Ultimate Providence, opening Golem Aruru (not searching it), or opening Unpossessed and even then, the turnover isn't terribly massive and gets diminishing returns the longer the game goes on. Fortunately with Unpossessed face up, attacks aren't encouraged anyway.

- Viability -
★★★☆☆
Legal Dridents will take you pretty far in Trinity. That said, most of the actual viability in this deck just comes from Aruru gamestates as cards in hand are very hard to deal with in Trinity. Our Extra Deck is loaded with powerful cards to convert the advantages provided from our Tuner roster and since the engine is so elegant and simple, I'd argue if you can concoct a brew that's simplier and even more oppressive, then the viability would skyrocket. Witchcrafters are therefore get 5★s in Versatility.


Pros:

  • Unfair Snowball: The Snowball provided from the various engines in the deck frankly aren't very fair when it comes to raw numbers advantage. You aren't necessarily seeing fresh cards each time; however, Haine combos being able to set herself up and get her revival are rather obnoxious gamestates to deal with. Every Witchcrafter Spell also recycling itself back to your hand/Field during your EP is extremely strong as well and helps us buffer decision making for Discard effects as we only stand to benefit from it in the end and maintain our generic Spells in hand. Lastly, if we find Spellbook Tower then free draws will take us even further with finding 2 fresh cards per turn and threating a minimum Genni most of the time.

  • Double Drident: Borreload Furious Dragon is something we can bring out as a 1 card combo thanks to Odd-Eyes Fusion. We can pretty comfortably destroy Scroll or Bystreet to search it since those cards will come back anyway.

Cons:

  • Rough Choke Points: Due to the linearity of the Apprentice's field effects, if you're at all disrupted during the process you go extremely negative, with Called By the Grave being the absolute worst offender and is a psuedo-FTK against you. We have a Garnet in Iris Swordsman and some of the Windwitches when drawn out of order as well but those are things that can be remedied.

  • Limited Interaction: Spell disruption isn't the best. Some things to consider are cards like Forbidden Chalice, Droplet, and Book of Moon/Sol & Luna for things of that avenue but even then, removal tends to be highly favored in comparison, especially for a deck like this that has to bait around Aruru or Discard for Haine to remove cards effectively.

  • Stat-Checked: Without Verre or the Fusion Monster, we get walled pretty hard by anything 2900 or greater, especially when summoned en masse. Under those situations we'll just have to do some juggling with Bystreet to protect our Haine as we slowly disect the board.

The mock-up's done. Let's review the basics.



OPENERS

This strategy features a few lines that we can access and still put up a reasonable enough threat, even if Haine has bricked us in some cases.

  • Haine-Haine: This is our boss monster at the time of the writing this due to the state of the banlist. Haine's pretty good nonetheless, she redirects all targeting effects to herself, is kinda big, and most importantly, wields a Drident effect for a Spell Discard. We can also send our Witchcrafter Continuous Spells for the cost as well while they're face-up on Field. She'll be trading one Spell each time to out a face-up Card; however, with the Witchcrafter Spells returning to us during EP, this is ultimately a non-issue. Even against the most cautious of players, this will always trade 1f1 in the short term and be a net +1 in the long term. If you're wondering about Eda, that Monster can grab us Witchcrafter Pittore who doubles as our stand-in for any 1500 DEF Spellcaster synergies.

  • Odd Inclusion of a Fusion: Borreload Furious Dragon can be summoned by the effect of Odd-Eyes Fusion by sending Odd-Eyes Venom Dragon and Odd-Eyes Rebellion Dragon Overload to the GY directly from our ED. Since all of our Apprentices enable Haine, we can just start with this and beam out Furious immediately (assuming the conditions are met) then play our turn as normal. If done while under the protection of Witchcrafter Bystreet (which a Schmietta opener gets us to anyway), then we can safely target any Witchcrafter monster on our side of the field for the effect of Furious Dragon to pop a free card on the opponent's side and keep the monster around. Double this up with Haine and we're getting 2 pops per turn with only 1 requiring use to actually lose a card (and at that point you can just send away the Bystreet as it cannot protect the Haine anymore and you'll just get it back during the next EP anyway!)

  • Charmed to Meet You: Spirit Charmers is still one of the silliest Spellcaster support cards that doesn't see use here despite working wonders for any Albaz deck. Nonetheless, we'll be using it to either setup Grand Spiritual Art - Ichirin, Unpossessed, Teamwork of the Possessed, or just Familiar-Possessed - Eria. We're only running one main deck Familiar-Possessed monster as they aren't that great and we aren't on their Continuous Spell, so be mindful that you can technically brick on this card if you find Eria first. If you're going to include a 2nd FP name to get around this, I recommend Aussa since it lets us pivot into literally any of our 1500 DEF targets without issue when destroyed under Unpossessed.

You should be opening any of these general setups with most hands with this deck but even in the event you find yourself with a Haine or Advance Dragon in hand, that's fine as well. You'll just have to pivot for going into turns 3+ for the most effective midgame you might be able to muster until your engine properly comes online.


MIDGAME

This is where the deck shines the most really and where the snowball tends to stack up to hilarious levels.

  • Windwitchcrafter: Outside of Windwitch - Glass Bell being a target for Unpossessed and related cards, we can go into Windwitch - Winter Bell by finding Glass or Windwitch - Ice Bell. Winter Bell will allow us to summon out Haine and any Apprentice in our hand for free during either player's battle phase simply by targeting itself. If that isn't needed, then we'll just pivot with Windwitch - Freeze Bell to summon Cyber Slash Harpy Lady and make her completely Battle Immune. Since we're cycling reliable Spells at the minimum, we'll be able to bounce something back on our own turns. Anything gained beyond that is honestly a given since this is still just going to remain on the field and demand removal answers. Lastly, if we find ourself not wanting to perform Windwitch lines or drawing them out of order somehow, we can just send them to the GY for the Summoning Condition of Awakening of the Possessed - Rasenryu and bounce back an opponent's card. Once we get rid of Rasenryu, we'll be able to grab any of our "Possessed" Spell/Traps right after, making this conversion pivot into all of our engines in the deck.

  • Advancing the Gamestate: Odd-Eyes Advance Dragon is our secondary target for Sky Iris' searching capabilities and can be Tribute Summoned by Tributing over Haine, Borreload Furious Dragon, Iris, etc. Since all of the monsters we play (besides the Magistus Extra Deck) should be assumed to have been summoned correctly, we can not only destroy and burn the opponent down, but also attack something with this 3k body and resummon most of our ED boss monsters or just Haine back with its revival effect. This is a very potent swing and represents a really large swing in LP as well.

  • Spell "Book": The Spellbook engine in this deck is very lite solely for the purposes of just cycling with Grand Spellbook Tower and/or having a way to Genni when the opponent is ultimately frustrated with the advantages provided by the Field Spell. It's worth mentioning that since our count of the spells isn't actually that high, any additional times we see the Spellbook spells will be random chance after bottom decking the Spell then shuffling via any search or deck summon effect.

The games may be drawn out and honestly the next section doesn't necesarily mean that you have to be a in deep grind game to take advantage of the following lines of play, just that they're good for closers if you haven't already won.


LATEGAME & CLOSERS

  • Mathematical: Zoroa, Ecclesia, Golden Swordsoul, and Glass Bell all allow us to access Synchros in this deck pretty comfortably. Being Level 4 Tuners enables us to just go into Geomathmech Magna and steal games with the insanity of its tempo swing. This card is extremely underrated and really potent just as an equalizer or way to clear 3 Monsters with one attack.

  • Arude Introduction: Witchcrafter Golem Aruru will win you games more than anything with an extremely lazy amount of effort required. Find this card and beat your opponent up with it. It's fine to even waste your Apprentices to summon this out during the opponent's MP1/2 if it means adding it to your hand during your upcoming SP. This card is really strong on its own.

  • The Power of Reliability: The Continuous Trap Witchcrafter Patronous is unmatched when it comes to grind game conversions (though it itself can run out of targets in the long game which is a bit funny to consider). It is our primary way of recycling our banished Apprentices or any instances of Haine being hit by Bottomless, Dinomischus, etc. When it's sent to the GY either due to the opponent, Schmietta, or our Magicians' Souls  (who can also send away our Field Spells and/or Scroll/Bystreet), we can cycle back any banished Spells that we might've used for Witchcrafter Genni's duplication ability. It's for this reason that if you find yourself opening Patronous or a way to it, you're incentivized to be greedy with Genni if it means you'll snowball sooner.

 


As you can tell from the guide the engines all talk to each other very well and operate on a level that's pretty silly when put into practice. Witchcrafter in Highlander will always run into the issue of the Spells doing virtually nothing (besides Scroll) without any of their archetypal monsters in play, but such is the sacrifices you make to try and put such strategies in the spotlight. Regardless, here's a few things to consider when coming up with your own brew!

Viability Boosters: Runick | Dragonmaid & Dragon Ruler | more Spellbook | Majespecter Spell/Traps | Albaz Support | Crossout Designator & all silver bullets

General Purpose: Chaos Creator, Magistus & Performages, Ancient Warriors - Ambitious Cao De, Xeno Meteorus, Loop of Destruction, Super Team Buddy Force Unite!, Duality

Legal Dridents will always be somewhat relevant and give the weaker archetypes of Trinity a leg to stand on, especially when they're as consistent to access as Haine or Moerk. The most important thing is to play into your deck's strengths and be sure to have a back-up plan in mind for one things go awry.

50 Card Deck = 4 Points with 4p used.
1p Witchcrafter Schmietta (Extra Copy)
1p Witchcrafter Patronous (Extra Copy)
1p Witchcrafter Golem Aruru
.5p Terraforming
.5p Last Will

Thanks for checking out my iteration of the Witchcrafter Starter for Trinity Format. In the event that Diabellestar winds up getting some cards back for us, then you might want to consider adding those cards in to make Haine even more oppressive. Nonetheless, good luck and take care.
Testing

deck_excerpt: Arise-Heart Mill FTK ft. Necroface+Card Destruction
deck_description:
Hey, whatsup? It seems like Arise-Heart has more than blasting the lands with C9 because Arise-Heart can also mill. Shocking, right?

 

 

Gameplan

1) Try discarding Necroface with Ravenous/Dugares. If not, you can target Necroface with "Allure of Darkness" later on but try to do so after you have used the ability of Saryuja, when you have four cards in your Main Deck.

2) Special Summon "Banisher of the Light" via Saryuja and Chaos Emperor Dragon with its ability to find combo pieces from Banish Zone (BZ) with "Primal Seed" cards later on. If Necroface is discarded via Ravenous/Dugares, pick it as DARK target for Chaos Emperor but don't banish Ancient as LIGHT target by accident at all.

3) Revive Ancient with "Monster Reborn". When you have two more monsters excluding Chaos Emperor, play "Galaxy Queen's Light" on Ancient to change the level of your monsters to 7.

4) XYZ Summon Arise-Heart and place "Xyz Territory" on Field Zone. When you have attached Necroface with Arise-Heart, you can return it to BZ by targeting Territory with MST.

5) With Necroface sent to BZ, you can mill your opponent. Rinse and repeat #4 until your opponent is out of cards. Also, for convenience, start the chain with Necroface and then Arise-Heart to return Necroface at where it belongs...

  • Technically, you don't have to utilize Arise-Heart. Having "Banisher of the Light" present and playing either "Extra Gate" or "Cost Down" to discard Necroface into BZ also accomplishes the same thing. You can remove "Xyz Territory" + "Galaxy Queen's Light" + "Mystical Space Typhoon" + "Monster Reborn" and give it a shot. Everything will remain the same as before.

6) To deck out your opponent for good measure, set "Primal Seed" + "Card Destruction" + "Contract with the Void". Then, play "Void >>> Destruction" combo and win the game.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Monster Reborn" is given for free, if you have played the tutorial to save 30 UR!

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Into The Void" + "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Primal Seed" + "Pot of Acquistiveness" + "Ravenous" + "Card Destruction" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 30 SR and 90 UR!

- "Number 60: Dugares the Timeless" can be found within "Number Recall" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Formula Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 60 SR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- As of this writing, "Kashtira Arise-Heart" is available on timed pack called "Flame of Fury". Hope you were lucky to find at least one copy to save 30 UR!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 510 SR and 180 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. If you have any questions, feel free to ask. Have fun in Master Duel!

Will notice some questionable deck choices here mainly no mirrorjade and the silly OEF tech choice. From someone whos used this deck as his petdeck forever Mirrorjade was just a card that never came up and didn't really fit the playstyle of the deck.


Branded Fusion in this deck is essentially instant fusion on steroids getting you the ambulo + a byblisp search + a big fusion (you'll lube into albion) on board to make Stapelia/Power with. This is a lot more bang for the card than Mirrorjade especially when the rest of the deck doesn't support the back and forth war of attrition story the Albaz lore embodies.


A lot of the flex spaces in the main deck went to cards that can 1 help chew through interractions and are good going first or 2nd although its understandable if you have to replace these due to price concerns.


Now onto Odd Eyes Fusion its similar utility to the main deck tech cards except only good 2nd but it gives you Venemy for free that along with eating through interrupts can be fused away for power fusions and brought back via pendulum summoning. I could see it being cut if you use the deck due to taking up 3 flex spots in the ED but hope you take it for a whirl.

deck_excerpt: Therion Sunavalon Rikka  / YCS Indianapolis Top 16
deck_description:
Category: Tournament Meta Decks (TCG)

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Yuhao Ye

Tournament: YCS Indianapolis – October 21st 2023

Placement: Top 16

Now that Generaiders are consistent AND good (and more importantly, have a sexy dommy waifu boss), and it's Spooktober, I finally decided to get around to posting this deck, one I actually have all the cards for. Before Vala, the gameplan was to get Boss Stage on the field afap, so you wanted the deck no bigger than the minimum, but with Vala that becomes the alternative. Now you can play proactively as well as reactively. After all, you can't Xyz Laevatein on your opponent's turn. I needed more level 9s to not brick on Vala, but the rest of the deck was too crucial to give up, so I slapped in two more. The deck doesn't technically need 3 Mardels, but I'm not putting in another Utgarda or a third of any other. And this way, you can combo off faster. Previously, I also ran 2 Hela, but she only pluses when you have tokens on the field. She is just here as another target. Same with Dovelgus, though he's already helped me out a lot.

With Boss Quest, you might be tempted to grab Stage and Room, but if you know your opponent is running a lot of removal, better grab that Fight instead for a backup Stage. You only really want to use Room's effect on a turn you Droll & Lock. Mardark is a level 9 that Theurlogical Demiurgy can summon. It debuffs enemy monsters, and recycles a Generaider for you to recycle Vala. It's also a wind monster for Link God Dragon. Condemned Witch nets you a Forbidden spell and summons Loptr on opponent's turn (this is not a combo I discovered). I pulled 1 Droplet from my Rise of the Duelist box and got the Chalice in a structure deck, and I am not about to buy more. 1 searchable copy of each fills this deck's needs anyway. Trias Hierarchia is a quick effect you want to use the tokens for. Kuji-Kiri Curse lets you use any level 9 from your hand or field, which can free up space to proc Vala for a new turn.

Now, I know I've said before that I don't like running handtraps in a deck if I can fill that space with engines instead, so some of you might be thinking, "Hey Flooffy, why do you have Droll & Lock Bird here?" Well that's because unlike almost any other deck, Generaiders can choose when the Droll & Lock activates. Instead of letting your opponent plus from all those draw 1 Generaider effects (something you only want them to do if you are playing a draw burn deck, like the casual Trickstar Generaider deck I concocted, which makes Frodi usable and I will post if anyone shows interest), they get stopped at +1 and won't get to search anything either. It also essentially turns Boss Room's effect into "negate that effect". Just remember you can't proc Jormungandr or Mardel after you do that.

Trickstars Foxglove Witch and Divaridis are remnants from that Trickstar Generaider deck because Foxglove is the only one that can be linked using generic Fairies (Loptr, Condemned Witch, Vala), and she summons Divaridis on death. I would save this for when you can end your opponent with the burn damage and their board is too pesky to attack or play through otherwise. The rest of the extra deck is filled with Xyz and link monsters you can summon, with plenty of big beatsticks for those obnoxious monsters unaffected by effects.

The side deck is full of alternative cards I mostly don't have, which all revolve around Mereologic Aggregator. He's a rank 9 that sends an extra deck monster to the gy on summon. The other cards in there do something if sent to the gy. N'tss: Target & destroy 1 card; Malong: Target & return 1 opponent's face-up card to the hand; Garura: Draw 1; Camellia (not yet released): Target 1 opponent's monster, ss her to their field, send targeted monster to gy, get control of her in end phase (says "must first be link summoned", don't know if that applies to summoning on your opponent's field, and switching control is not summoning); Kaleido-Heart: Ss her, then target and shuffle 1 opponent's card (I actually pulled one from a blister at Walmart, so I'm really excited to use her). You could just play it safe and only run monsters you can summon naturally by bumping up Aggregator to 2, using him to proc his own gy effect faster.

If there's one card you can cut from this deck, it's Boss Room. I just like the interaction with Droll & Lock.

deck_excerpt: Number 43 FTK ft. Linewalker+Destructive Draw+Oracle King
deck_description:
Greetings! In this deck, we will try to FTK our opponent with Number 43 but there is a twist: We will unload the damage ourselves to convert into healing and reflect it. I have tried with Skull Invitation before, so this isn't news to me but if it's to you, read the guide for further info.

 

 

Gameplan

1) Set your opponent's LP to 3000 with Linewalker. If you have XYZ Summoned Number 13, send it as Tribute for Cusillu. Otherwise, use Number 13 as Link material for Saryuja.

2) Revive Number 13 with "Monster Reborn" and overlay into Number 43 with "Rank-Up-Magic Launch". Then, activate Swirl when you also have Ghost to Fusion Summon Oracle King by using Swirl + Ghost as Fusion materials.

3) Play "Temple of the Kings >>> Destructive Draw" combo. Then, destroy "Destructive Draw" with Ravenous to inflict 3000 damage to yourself...

  • Or, is it? When Oracle King is around, you can convert 3000 damage into healing. With Number 43, you can deal 3000 damage to your opponent for the FTK.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Monster Reborn" is given for free, if you have completed the tutorial to save 30 UR!

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

Cyber end dragon strat
PS19 Skill Drain

(Disclaimer: Think slow but act quick. You should practice in PvE mode before stepping into PvP. If you feel like Ranked (300 sec) isn't enough, you can definitely make it on time while playing Casual within 480 sec time limit.)

It's time to feed your cat and care Melffy well. With proper treatment, it can be vicious and bring terror with C9. Without further ado, let's have a blast!

 

 

Gameplan

1) Place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon to find combo pieces from Banish Zone (BZ) with "Primal Seed" cards. Under no circumstance, don't banish either Formula or Ancient as LIGHT target for Chaos Emperor but you can banish any DARK target.

2) Link Summon Reprodocus and revive 2 x Formula with "Monster Reborn". Then, play "Temple of the Kings >>> DNA Surgery" combo to change the type of all monsters on the battlefield to Beast. This step is a must to XYZ Summon Melffy and its attachment ability. You are welcome to destroy Temple with MST, by the way.

3) XYZ Summon Melffy by using 2 x Formula as materials, pointing towards where Reprodocus is. You can start repeating these steps until you think it's enough...

  • Your aim is to let Melffy have at least 10 materials. With "DNA Surgery" changing everything to Beast, you can attach anything.
  • Since the attachment ability of Melffy isn't hard once per turn, it can be reset via Book spells.
  • "Monster Reborn" can grant resources for Melffy.

4) Revive Ancient with "Monster Reborn" and place Xiangsheng on Pendulum Zone. With Xiangsheng, you can change the Rank of Melffy to 7 by targeting Ancient and Melffy.

5) Activate Reprodocus to change the attribute of Melffy to "LIGHT". Next, activate "Clockwork Night" to overwrite the type of all monsters on the battlefield to Machine. (Big thanks to Triki for type change tactics)

6) From Rank 2 EARTH Beast to Rank 7 LIGHT Machine, you can lead the way to C9. Start off with "Astral Force" to overlay into "Number 9" and then, C9 with "Barian's Force".

7) You can take off the pants of C9 and unload big amount of damage for the FTK.

My Centurion Adventure Deck
hi

After seeing the Horus back in July when they first got spoiled, I knew they'd be just what Therions need to have some more variety in how you play them and generally being a powerful engine overall. However, P.U.N.K. will always be great with Therions ever since the release of Diabolantis cranking the deck up to 11. So, I sat down and thought to myself, "Por que no los dos?"

Thus, Therion Horus P.U.N.K. was born! Utilizing the pitch effect that Imsety and King's Sarc have on top of the the P.U.N.K. engine to going into Diabolantis, send Lily, then reviving Rising Carp or Foxy Tune to go into the typical plays. What really draws me to this list, however, is the consistency and the wealth of plays. What this deck is capable of is awesome.

Now, does it get clapped by Nib? It honestly depends. There are hands that can, but there are also hands that give you a King before your 5th summon with extensions. Not super common, but it ain't once in a blue moon.

The only "problem child" card I can think of is Dark Ruler, which sucks if you go first, but the deck has ways to break boards going second, so it's all good. Winnig or losing the dice roll kind of determines which Xyz monster you go into.

Also, whenever I get the whole list in paper, I want to make a video discussing the list and going over some combos for it. For now, enjoy it here and please use it for reference, if you'd like!

deck_excerpt: Number 43 FTK ft. Black Garden+Token Thanksgiving
deck_description:
It's time to pay homage to Number 43. We can't thank Number 43 enough that he wanted to have a feast with tokens.

 

 

Gameplan

1) Place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon to find combo pieces from Banish Zone (BZ) with "Primal Seed" cards. Don't forget to activate "Black Garden" as well.

2) Special Summon Sharnga >>> Vata >>> Caligo, in explained order. If you lack Main Monster Zones (MMZ), clear anything but Chaos Emperor with "Offerings to the Doomed". Then, XYZ Summon Number 43 with these three. You can also repeat this step for another time by reviving the trio with "Monster Reborn".

3) With lots of Special Summoning thanks to "Monster Reborn" and whatnot, when Number 43 monster(s) is/are here, activate "Token Thanksgiving" to destroy all tokens and heal up for 5 x 800 = 4000 in total. Thanks to Number 43, you can convert healing into damage. Repeat this step until the opponent is dead for the FTK...

  • If you go second, clear your opponent's monsters with Offerings first, so that "Black Garden" can plant more roses to opposing side.
  • When you have used the ability of Number 43, you can destroy it with Offerings and revive with "Monster Reborn" to reset it.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Sharnga" + "Vata" can be collected by purchasing "Blackwing's Pride" deck. 60 UR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Black Garden" can be found within "Exquisite Jet-Black Rose" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Primal Seed" + "Pot of Acquistiveness" + "Ravenous" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 60 SR and 60 UR!

- "Number 60: Dugares the Timeless" can be found within "Number Recall" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Formula Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 510 SR and 210 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

deck_excerpt: Master the Ham, Become the Ham
deck_description:
Master of Ham is an absolutely amazing card for any Flip Deck to have access to. For one, it is a Level 5 Fusion Monster which means that you can use Instant Fusion to get it out of the Extra Deck, and in doing so, you can Special Summon a Flip Monster from the Deck in face-down Defense Position. That could've been all that was written on the card, but it has another effect which allows you to banish 2 Flip Monsters from GY and/or face-up field to Special Summon it from GY in face-down Defense Position. And to make things even better, it's first effect to Summon a Flip Monster from Deck face-down activates on Fusion Summon or when it flips face-up which means that you can just do it again on a future turn. Master of Ham fixes one of the key issues within Prediction Princess which is your inability to easily access Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Your previously most consistent options were World Legacy Monstrosity, Spirit of the Fall Wind, and Pot of Prosperity. If we utilize Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio and Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra to search Instant Fusion from the Deck, we will be able to have access to Master of Ham getting Prediction Princess Bibliomuse from Deck while also giving you enough material on field to either end on an I:P Masquerena or even a 3 material Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess. 

Main Deck: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotreith and 2 Prediction Princess Tarotrei. I will usually recommend playing 4 or 5 Prediction Princes Ritual Monsters, being a combination of some number of each. Tarotreith can be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei's End Phase effect. On flip, it can Special Summon a Flip Monster from Deck face-down and it can Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters either face-up or face-down. Imagine this card as Tarotrei who can flip multiple monsters at a time which means that you can definitely start with this card instead of Tarotrei and get access to Tarotrei later in your combo during your Turn to have her on field. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster either face-up or face-down and she can also Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY in face-down Defense Position during the End Phase. 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Bibliomuse gives targeting and destruction protection to all of your Ritual Monsters. On flip, it searches a Prediction Princess monster and a Ritual Spell from your Deck to your hand, and if it is Tributed and sent to GY, you can Special Summon it back face-down. 2 Deus-X Krawler which negates the activated effects of all face-up monsters your opponent field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed, you can add a monster with a different type and attribute from it from your Deck to your hand. 1 Mardel, Generaider Boss of Light which searches a Generaider card or a Plant monster from your Deck to your hand on Summon. Mardel is here as a Level 9 target for World Legacy Monstrosity to target on field or to to Summon from Deck using it. 2 Lonefire Blossom which can Tribute a Plant to Summon a Plant from Deck. This basically acts as 2 extra copies of Ophrys Scorpio and it can also Summon Mardel from Deck which gives you a Level 9 target on field for Monstrosity. 3 Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio and 1 Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra. Scorpio can send a monster from hand to GY on Normal or Special Summon to Special Summon a Predaplant monster from Deck. If Cobra is Special Summoned by the effect of a Predaplant monster, it can add a Poly or a Fusion Spell from Deck to hand. Scorpio Summons Cobra from Deck and Cobra searches Instant Fusion which gets you Master of Ham. But something that is even better is the fact that Scorpio and Cobra will remain on field. This gives you 2 material worth of Link Material or they can act as 2 Level 3 monsters for a Number 75: Bamboozling Gossip Shadow which can insulate you against a handtrap monster. 3 Diviner of the Herald which sends a Fairy from Deck or Extra Deck to the GY on Normal or Special Summon and gains Levels equal to the sent monster's Level. This sends Herald of the Arc Light from Extra Deck for a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell search. And finally, 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring.

Spell/Traps: 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which Ritual Summons a Prediction Princess from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can also banish it during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess from Deck face-down. 2 World Legacy Monstrosity which can Special Summon a Level 9 monster form hand or target a Level 9 monster on field and Special Summon 2 Level 9 monsters with a different type and attribute from Deck. This can get you material for a Rank 9 out onto the field for something like a Mereologic Aggregator if you still need to search for Ritual cards, but it can also get you Bibliomuse out onto the field and into rotation in case you did not have access to Master of Ham. 1 Instant Fusion which Special Summons a Level 5 or lower Fusion from Extra Deck which is treated as a Fusion Summon. This gets you Master of Ham which is what you really want in this Deck. 2 Triple Tactics Thrust and 2 Triple Tactics Talent. 3 Pot of Prosperity and 3 Infinite Impermanence.

Extra Deck: 1 Master of Ham which is just so good for reasons I've already stated. 2 Herald of the Arc Light which adds a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell from Deck when it is sent to GY. 1 Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder. 1 Infinitrack Earth Slicer which can detach any number of materials to destroy an equal number of cards on field and it can also attach any monster it destroys by battle to itself as Xyz Material which makes it great for board clearing and making Zeus. 1 Mereologic Aggregator which sends a monster from Extra Deck to GY on Xyz Summon which can be Herald for a Ritual Search and it can detach any number of materials to attach the same number of monsters from GY to it as material which can loop Herald for Ritual searches if needed. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity as a Rank 9 you can go into for interruption. 1 Number 75: Bamboozling Gossip Shadow which can replace your opponent's activated monster effect with "each players draw a card" which can fade a monster handtrap for protection or you can also just use it as interruption also. 1 Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax. 1 Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess. 1 I:P Masquerena. 1 S:P Little Knight. 1 Sky Striker Ace - Camellia which can Summon itself to your opponent's field and send a monster your opponent controls to GY if it is sent to GY. You don't really need this card, but it turns Masquerena's Link Summon effect into a lot more interruption, and it is even generic. 1 Cross-Sheep which we are usually going to use either its Fusion or Ritual effect. If a monster is Special Summoned to a zone it points to, if it points to a Fusion, it can Summon back a Level 4 or lower monster from GY or draw 2 cards and discard 2 cards in the case of pointing to a Ritual. You can make this card with Scorpio and Cobra, Instant Fusion Master of Ham to a zone it points to, trigger Cross-Sheep to bring back either Scorpio or Cobra, giving you your Bibliomuse access as well as material for a 3 material Apollousa for 3 monster negates. 

Side Deck: 2 Nibiru, the Primal Being. 3 Thunder King, the Lightningstrike Kaiju, 1 Triple Tactics Thrust, 2 Dark Ruler No More, 2 Lightning Storm, 1 Harpie's Feather Duster, 3 Evenly Matched, and 1 Dimensional Barrier.

deck_name: Fun and stable Blue-Eyes deck for Master duel and irl (swap out maxx c for irl)
deck_excerpt: Blue-Eyes supremacy! A Very fun deck with decently consistant starters and a spicy extra deck :)
deck_description:
This is mainly based off of the cards that I own irl and what I enjoy using. It is still a pretty decent deck, but obviously there are better/more expensive cards that you could implement. It also goes without saying that Blue-Eyes is bricky and pretty unreliable... But thats not why we play it, it's about falling in style!

The OG Ultimate dragon is just there as I bought a JUMP secret rare for nostaglia and also so I can summon him for an epic anime moment, lol.

Dragon Shrine to send a vanilla Blue-Eyes and Abyss for the double search is amazing to get Chaos Form and Chaos Max for that spicy summon on your next turn.

Feather Duster is there as I have no back row destruction.

You can also throw a Called By in for the second Jet Dragon if you wish, or a 3rd Melody for one of the Dragon Shrines.

As stated in the title, Maxx C is only in here as I have been playing this predominantly on Master Duel, but irl I would use Ash.

I'd be happy if even 1 person appreciates this deck list :)

Good day!

NATURIA RUNICK DECK MASTER DUEL - Season 22

https://youtu.be/fy5jg1U70GM

This is a normal agent combo deck. Its been my favort deck when lost santury came out all those years ago. And this is so far my years of playtesting and working on this deck with only a budge for it. Now im posting it here to get some feed back on improvements, PS plese try and keep them cheap i know some cards i would love to use but am waiting to look at how to pay for them. Down side i have seen well playing the deck is its know to brick, it has little to no card draw, and can be easy to stop with one interuption. so im asking for any advice for start fixing at least one or two of this problems?

* Combos/Tips: 

 

1.- Carrocería de maquinaria (Machina gearframe) y Maquinaria fortaleza (Machina fortress):

  • Se juega de modo normal a Carrocería de maquinaria y buscamos a la mano una Maquinaria ciudadela en el mazo.

  • Jugamos de modo especial a Maquinaria fortaleza, descartando de la mano a Maquinaria ciudadela.

  • OPCIONAL: Se podría equipar la Carrocería de maquinaria a la Maquinaria fortaleza, para poder protegerlo, e independiente si va a morir una máquina u otra, se activará la habilidad especial de Maquinaria ciudadela para que aparezca en campo.

 

2.- Maquinaria fortaleza (Machina fortress), un Reciclador de chatarra (Scrap recycler) y cualquiera otro monstruo:

  • Invocar normal al Reciclador de chatarra y mandamos con su efecto al cementerio, una Maquinaria ciudadela.

  • Se invoca de modo especial a la Maquinaria fortaleza, seleccionando a ella misma y a la otra máquina que tengamos en mano, descartando a ambos, y así poder invocar a la misma Maquinaria fortaleza, ya que con su modo especial, puede seleccionarse a sí misma para invocarse.

 

3.- Carrocería de maquinaria (Machina gearframe), Maquinaria fortaleza (Machina fortress) y Maquinaria a toda marcha (Machina overdrive):

  • Se juega de modo normal a Carrocería de maquinaria y buscamos a la mano una Maquinaria ciudadela en el mazo.

  • Jugamos de modo especial a Maquinaria fortaleza, descartando de la mano a Maquinaria ciudadela.

  • Jugamos boca abajo la trampa Maquinaria a toda marcha y se termina el turno.

  • En turno oponente, podremos interrumpirlo con la trampa Maquinaria a toda marcha, y seleccionamos la Carrocería de maquinaria para destruirla e invocar de modo especial desde el mazo a Maquinaria incursora aérea. Cómo Carrocería de maquinaria fue destruida, se invoca al campo desde el cementerio a Maquinaria ciudadela.

  • Aun en turno oponente, se podrá realizar el efecto de Maquinaria incursora aérea, seleccionandola a ella misma para destruirla e invocar de modo especial desde el mazo a Megaforma de maquinaria.

 

4.- Redistribución de la maquinaria, Maquinaria ciudadela y cualquier otro monstruo de nivel 8 o superior:

  • Jugamos la magia Redistribución de la maquinaria descartando de la mano a la Maquinaria ciudadela, para buscar en el mazo al monstruo Carrocería de maquinaria y la trampa Maquinaria a toda marcha.

  • Se juega de modo normal a Carrocería de maquinaria y buscamos a la mano una Maquinaria fortaleza en el mazo.

  • Invocamos de modo especial a Maquinaria Fortaleza, descartando al monstruo de nivel 8 en la mano.

  • Jugamos la trampa Maquinaria a toda marcha boca abajo para repetir el combo/tips número 3.

deck_name: 60 Card Dragon Link! (MD October 2023, Duelist Cup LVL 20)
deck_excerpt: Dragon Link, explained! Can get to Master 1 and Duelist Cup Level 20!
deck_description:
Dragon, dragon, rock the dragon! Dragon Link Z!

Dragon Link is a deck near and dear to my heart ever since I picked it up a few months ago. The lengthy combos and relatively expressive deckbuilding enable a lot of fun to be had for me, and it can play against just about every deck in the format (with caveats). It's in contention for one of the best decks in the format, I'd argue it's better than Kashtira by virtue of consistency (even this 60 card brew I found bricks less than Kashtira) and is at least competitive with Purrely and Labrynth, and will remain as a powerful option going forward for some time. Without any further ado, here's the card by card and why I chose things.

Main Deck Dragon Link (Rokket, Chaos Dragons, and Seyfert)

  • 3x Rokket Tracer. The lifeblood of our deck, not our best normal but a card we would absolutely love to see in our opening hand regardless. With Striker Dragon, you can 1 card combo into Chaos Ruler (or any other DARK level 8 Synchro) using this card.
  • 2x Rokket Recharger. We need something to summon off Tracer's effect, and Recharger is basically the best option. I run two to avoid situations where I draw Recharger and can't use Tracer's effect to summon anything.
  • 1x Absorouter Dragon. Send this to the grave to search a Rokket (usually Tracer). Especially nice when paired with Chaos Space or Dragon Ravine, to make the cost of those cards completely beneficial.
  • 1x Noctovision Dragon. Extender, gives you a draw when used as Link material. Don't run more than 1, as it is a brick on its own, but it's good enough to have 1 copy.
  • 1x Boot Sector Launch. Field Spell to SS up to two Rokkets with different names straight from hand, searchable by our Link-1? Amazing. This enables Rokket Tracer to do some silly things by summoning it from hand and then being the target to blow up for its effect.
  • 3x Quick Launch. Extension, a starter, a way to play around Maxx C a little, it's another card we cannot go without. Amazing.
  • 3x Starliege Seyfert. Fill up the graveyard and search a Dragon of the same level as the ones you discarded? Don't mind if I do. Generally, we send a Level 4 (preferably something in hand, but Seyfert works in a pinch) to search out one of the two Level 4 Chaos Dragons in order to have comfortable plays. Seyfert represents our only outright one card combo into Borrelend, so we absolutely have to run three copies. Also lets you retrieve a Level 8 LIGHT/DARK Dragon from grave and add it to hand.
  • 3x White Dragon Wyverburster. Banish a DARK from grave to summon this. After that, you Link (or Synchro) it off to search...
  • 2x Black Dragon Collapserpent. Banish a LIGHT from grave to summon this. We run fewer since most of our deck is DARK and it can occasionally be a brick to open with.
  • 1x Chaos Dragon Levianeer. One of our high roll big boys. Banish all DARKs to handrip, Banish LIGHTs and DARKs to destroy up to two cards on field (good for board breaking and getting ready for a turn 3 OTK), Banish all LIGHTs to Monster Reborn (we rarely use this due to lack of LIGHTs in deck and the low impactness of it, but it can be useful on occasion).
  • 3x Chaos Space. We play a lot of LIGHT/DARK monsters that can't be normalled, so of course we run this. Ideally we'd discard Saronir/Absorouter to search our Wyverburst, but use your judgement to decide what should be sent for its effect. The grave effect to draw is also really useful, since it represents both recovery and resource accumulation.

Bystials (or, how I learned to stop worrying and love the Branded Beast)

  • 1x Bystial Lubellion. Searches a Bystial of choice, can summon itself from grave by tributing a Level 6+ DARK Dragon, and can then put a Branded Continuous Spell/Trap straight from deck onto the field face-up. The exact number of copies is a bit flexible, I run 1 due to economics (UR dust typically being spent on new decks and new cards rather than extra copies) but more copies are certainly nice to have.
  • 1x Bystial Magnamhut. Probably what you're searching with Lubellion, though the choice is going to be dependent on board state. It searches a Dragon in the end phase after summoning, and it means any Dragon. Generally, when you're going first you'll be searching another Bystial in the end phase (Druiswurm or Baldrake, probably). I'd run at least two copies if it weren't limited, but alas I don't control the banlist.
  • 1x Bystial Druiswurm. Our boardbreaking Bystial, this one often forces immediate attention from the opponent due to its effect when sent from field to grave. I'd probably run a second copy over Baldrake if this wasn't limited, but YMMV on that front.
  • 1x Bystial Baldrake. Theoretically a really nasty monster that can supremely ruin your opponent's day, but it's just ever-so-slightly too specific with its requirements to consistently be a nuisance. Still good, though, and it's more importantly a Bystial (meaning it can do the anti-LIGHT/DARK banish, making Tear players miserable and Mathmech players seethe).
  • 2x Bystial Saronir. Send this to the grave, send another Bystial/Branded card to the grave. I usually send Lubellion, unless I already have Lubellion in the grave or a way to get it into rotation (in which case I send Branded Regained).
  • 1x Branded Regained. Gives you both what's basically Chaos Space's GY effect every turn and revives a Bystial from grave when your opponent summons a monster.
  • 1x Branded Beast. A pop to any card on the field, provided you control a Bystial and have a Dragon to tribute. Also grabs a Branded Continuous Spell/Trap from GY and puts it back on the field in the end phase, allowing you to get Regained on the field alongside it. This and Regained represent a pretty nasty control engine, allowing grind games to be extremely smooth, while allowing you to also break boards with Beast's effect.

Other Main Deck Dragon Engine (Dragonmaid, Red-Eyes, Dragon Ravine)

  • 3x Chamber Dragonmaid. Another one card combo into Romulus, a searcher for the extremely good Dragonmaid Tidying (excellent disruption on your opponent's turn), and a Level 4 to Synchro with Tracer (or the Bystials for Chaos Angel, more on that later). Just an all-around good card for Dragon Link and the 60 card variants get to use this well since we have a lot more space for this kind of thing than 40 card variants.
  • 1x Dragonmaid Hospitality. Our revive for Chamber, part of the aformentioned one card combo. NS Chamber, search this, Link into Striker, use Hospitality to revive Chamber, link both her and Striker for Romulus.
  • 1x Dragonmaid Tidying. Bounce both a Dragon you control and a card on your opponent's field or GY. Just solid disruption that gets around destruction protection and can then be used to summon Chamber from hand/GY on the next turn.
  • 1x Black Metal Dragon. One for One target, and also an NS that can net you Romulus with no further investment (beyond banishing Striker Dragon).
  • 1x Red-Eyes Darkness Metal Dragon. Banish a Dragon on field to summon this, then you can use it to summon a Dragon from your hand/GY. Allows a lot of stuff and enables some truly wacky high roll plays, but is a brick on its own.
  • 1x One for One. Technically non-engine, but since we're only using it to summon Black Metal it may as well just be put here.
  • 1x Dragon Ravine. Searchable via Romulus, allows us to Foolish Burial any Dragon for the cost of a discard.

Non-Engine (Handtraps, anti-Handtraps, and Thrust targets)

  • 3x Ash Blossom, 3x Maxx C, 2x Called By the Grave. It's Master Duel, we have to be prepared for anything and Ash+Called By is basically that. Maxx C is also there, for obvious reasons. I'd run like eight copies of Called By if I could (not actually that many, but you get the idea), we suffer whenever any of the big three blowout handtraps resolve (Maxx C, Droll & Lock Bird, and Dimensional Shifter) and it counters all of them.
  • 1x Crossout Designator to stop other handtraps. Most importantly, Nibiru can screw us if we don't have a particularly good hand (as we have very few combo lines to play under the threat of Nibiru), and Designator is the best counter to it.
  • 1x Nibiru. Ruins other combo decks' day, we need a copy for Crossout Designator, and being a LIGHT means it can be grabbed off Chaos Ruler and banished by the Chaos monsters to summon them.
  • 3x Triple Tactics Thrust. Searches any Normal Spell/Trap if your opponent activates a monster effect, though you can only add it to your hand (instead of setting it for next turn) if your opponent controls a monster. This card made a big splash on release in the OCG, and of course it's extremely good here where we need tools for basically every situation.
  • 1x Herald of the Abyss. Anti-Purrely and Kashtira measures, and our solution to Towers-type monsters in general.
  • 1x Harpie's Feather Duster. Anti-backrow. We do have a fair amount of backrow hate (Branded Beast, Chaos Angel, Tidying, Levianeer), but it requires set up we often don't have the luxury of doing against backrow decks so Duster solves that.
  • 1x That Grass Looks Greener. It's a 60 card deck, of course we run Grass. That juicy, juicy mill 20 is too much to pass up.
  • 1x Triple Tactics Talent. Versatile card, can unbrick you if you get Ashed, steal a key monster to force interaction or allow you to break boards, or let you look at your opponent's hand and rip a card out of it.
  • 1x Evenly Matched. While not quite as potent as it was previously due to Kashtira and Purrely having extremely potent single boss monsters, Evenly is still a phenomenal boardbreaker.
  • 2x Infinite Impermanence. It negates a monster on-field and can be used from hand. Good for both stopping your opponent from building a board and for boardbreaking.

Extra Deck (it's just the whole Extra)

  • 2x Striker Dragon. Searches Boot Sector Launch, can grab a Rokket from grave if need be, and the Link arrow is useful for...
  • 1x Guardragon Pisty. The only Guardragon Link to not be banned, and still extremely good. If two Link monsters have arrows pointing to a monster zone, you can summon any Dragon from your GY or banished cards to that zone. Just note you cannot summon anything but Dragons while Pisty is on the field.
  • 1x Dragunity Knight - Romulus. Searches Dragon Ravine, and that's often it. Its second effect to summon a Dragon from hand can be useful, but only in certain scenarios where you can get into a Synchro without screwing up your combo.
  • 1x Hieratic Seal of the Heavenly Spheres. It's an FTK. Jokes aside, it's basically our best option when put under Maxx C and makes Nibiru hurt less if we're hit by it. Tribute it to bounce an opponent's card, then summon Druiswurm/Magnamhut depending on the situation.
  • 1x Dharc the Dark Charmer, Gloomy. In situations where you're DARK-locked by Rokket Tracer, this is the best DARK Link-2 to make. It's rare you'll actually summon anything off his effect, but it can occasionally come in handy.
  • 1x Triple Burst Dragon. To set up Pisty's effect, and also equip to Borreload Savage Dragon.
  • 1x Knightmare Unicorn. For situations where you need something off the field and can go into it. Entirely replacable if desired.
  • 1x Accesscode Talker. OTK push tool if needed, entirely replaceable.
  • 1x Borrelend Dragon. Our big boss, the goal of our combos, the thing we strive to make every turn. Can't be destroyed, attack all monsters on the field once, negate a monster on the field permanently and revive a Rokket from the grave. This card is absurd, and you should always strive to get into it if possible.
  • 1x Number 38: Hope Harbinger Dragon Titanic Galaxy. Replacable if desired, but we can sometimes make a Rank 8 and it's either this or The Zombie Vampire, and I prefer shoring up my endboards via this guy.
  • 1x Chaos Ruler the Chaotic Magical Dragon. Shockingly, this card isn't banned. And thank goodness, because it's a phenomenal card for this. It allows us to try and fix an otherwise really bad hand, and allows us to high-roll into some stupid stuff. Also revives itself by banishing a LIGHT and a DARK, which can be useful for Link material.
  • 1x Borreload Savage Dragon. Omni-negate on a Synchro we can easily make, provided we have a Link in grave to equip. Can also beat over a lot of monsters thanks to it gaining half the Attack of the equipped Link monster.
  • 1x Baronne de Fleur. Due to being WIND and us frequently DARK-locking ourselves, we rarely summon it, but Rokket Tracer+a Bystial can make this easily.
  • 1x Chaos Angel. Doesn't even need a tuner and can become a Towers if you use a LIGHT. More importantly, just banishes a card from the field without any cost on summon, making it great for cracking boards. A Bystial+any Level 4 in the deck gets us this.

Future Cards

  • Bystial Dis Pater is a great Level 10 Synchro that provides extension, interaction, and recovery. Most brews I've seen post CYAC run this in the OCG/TCG, and we'll be running it the moment it comes out in MD since we can easily make it.
  • S:P Little Knight. A stupidly good staple ED monster, though it being Link-2 (with very poor Link arrows) does mean this deck doesn't quite use it as well as it'd like. Still worth looking into.
  • Etude of the Branded. We often summon back Rokket Tracer with Borrelend, we frequently have Bystials on field, we aren't usually DARK-locked on our opponent's turn, Etude allows a quick Synchro on either turn to summon whatever you desire. It's also a Macro Cosmos for monsters used as material for Ritual/Fusion/Synchro/Link monsters, which is situationally useful. It might be worth looking into, but probably not something to main deck.
  • The Bystial Aluber. Is very bad. Bafflingly bad, and I would not recommend running it for any reason.

deck_excerpt: Reversal Quiz FTK ft. Zexal Alliance
deck_description:
Hello! It has been a while since I shared another Reversal Quiz deck. This time, it will be with "Zexal Alliance". Let me explain.

 

 

Gameplan

1) XYZ Summon "Number 39: Utopia" by using 2 x Cthugua as materials and place Utopia anywhere but center. Reason is that center will be reserved for Yajiro.

2) Special Summon Yajiro via Saryuja. You have to place Yajiro at the center or he will explode.

3) After placing "Temple of the Kings" and "Zexal Alliance" where they are safe from Yajiro's sight, give Yajiro to your opponent with "Shien's Spy", one square to either left or right with respect to where Utopia is...

  • If you go second, use Raigeki/Ravenous to clear your opponent's side. You need at least two adjacent free columns, one of which should be where Yajiro and Utopia points to.

4) Play "Limited Barian's Force" to overlay into "Number C39: Utopia Ray V" and place it to where Utopia was...

  • Actually, you don't have to use "Limited Barian's Force" at all. If you have "Number C39: Utopia Ray", seen in "Side Deck", you can simply overlay with it. I just forgot I had this card, how silly of me.

5) If you did everything right, C39 will be destroyed by Yajiro. Then, you can activate "Zexal Alliance" to set your LP to 10 and place any card on top of your deck. Don't forget to bring "Number 39: Utopia" with "Zexal Alliance", otherwise it won't work...

  • To not miss out anything, change the button on the lower right corner of the screen to either "ON" or "Auto". It can be changed within settings under "Duel", where you can change "Activation Confirmation" to "Switch + Hold" for manual setup.

6) Set "Fuhma Shuriken" and activate "Reversal Quiz". Choose correct answer from what you have done via "Zexal Alliance" for the FTK!

deck_description:
(Disclaimer: Think slow but act quick. You should practice in PvE mode before stepping into PvP. If you feel like Ranked (300 sec) isn't enough, you can definitely make it on time while playing Casual within 480 sec time limit.)

Good day to you! I decided to improve Magical Thorn deck I made a long time ago. With "Primal Seed" and "Magical Contract Door" at your side, it doesn't matter if you go first or second. Let me show you.

 

 

Gameplan

1) When you have Ravenous present, place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon to find combo pieces from Banish Zone (BZ) with "Primal Seed" cards later on.

2) To win, we need to give our opponent cards and they should have at least 10 cards to make this OTK viable. Start by playing "The Humble Sentry" to shuffle other Chaos Emperor into your deck and then, play "Magical Contract Door" to tutor Chaos Emperor and give your opponent any spell but combo pieces and Quick-Play spells. You can also give any two of your cards with "Gold Moon Coin" to your opponent as well. Anyways, here are these spells in question, of which under any circumstances, you mustn't give them at all:

  • Combo: Primal Seed + The Humble Sentry + Magical Contract Door
  • Quick-Play: Reload + Pot of Acquisitiveness

3) When you think it's enough, destroy ME-PSY-YA with Ravenous. Then, set all traps and end your turn. This step is a must because we have given lots of spells to the opponent and "Magical Thorn" deals damage if they were sent to GY, not BZ.

4) On your opponent's turn of Draw Phase, activate "Present Card" first and follow-up with "Magical Thorn" cards for the FTK. You see, "Cannon Soldier" is banned in MD because you can tribute anything to deal damage but for some reason, "Man-Thro' Tro" isn't because you can only tribute Normal Monsters to deal damage. deck_excerpt: Use unique noble knight starters to create powerful end boards in this modernized classic
deck_description:
<!-- [if !supportLists]-->T        

<!--[endif]-->Intro and Camelot Breakdown

So infernoble knight noble knight has been a pet project of mine ever since the newest wave of infernoble knights was announced. I’ve already made a video on the subject before but the TCG decided to bless us with the brand new exclusive card: Camelot, Realm of the Noble Knights and Noble Arms. Camelot got me really going with the deck. Despite a questionable first glance, this card is honestly very solid for the architype. We can break it down into a few key things.Replaces Unexpected Dai for access to the normal monster and extenders.

<!-- [if !supportLists]-->1.       <!--[endif]-->Camelot is fully an extender

<!-- [if !supportLists]-->2.       <!--[endif]-->Searchable by a ton of cards

<!-- [if !supportLists]-->a.       <!--[endif]-->(Noble Arms Museum, Heritage of the chalice, Noble Knight Borz, Ignoble Knight of Black Laundsallyn)

<!-- [if !supportLists]-->3.       <!--[endif]-->Replays itself a turn after use and is re-useable

<!-- [if !supportLists]-->4.       <!--[endif]-->Searches the Infernoble Arms or any Noble Arms card

<!-- [if !supportLists]-->5.       <!--[endif]-->No restrictions

<!-- [if !supportLists]-->6.       <!--[endif]-->Destruction protection

<!-- [if !supportLists]-->a.       <!--[endif]-->Can help cheese through some disruptions.

<!-- [if !supportLists]-->7.       <!--[endif]-->Requires 2 bricks

<!-- [if !supportLists]-->8.       <!--[endif]-->Pulls out Noble knights of the round table

<!-- [if !supportLists]-->a.       <!--[endif]-->Dump a noble knight to grave at end of turn

<!-- [if !supportLists]-->b.      <!--[endif]-->Potential I:P Masquerena fodder

<!-- [if !supportLists]-->c.       <!--[endif]-->Late game recursion and draw

Noble Knights of the Round Table is very odd. It’s not good but it is free. Realistically we can use the noble knight dump effect every turn. I’ve got 1 or two techs to take advantage of that. Typically though you’ll just be dumping an Infernoble Knight Turpin for better recursion. The second effect is not needed or good. But in unique situations you can use it to put out fodder for I;P masquerna. Remember this can trigger the infernoble knight equips when sent to the graveyard. The 9 and 12 effects do happen if the game goes beyond the first turn. This is a rogue deck in modern yugioh so that’s very questionable and shouldn’t be depended on.

Overall Camelot is one of the best-designed legacy support cards I’ve seen so far. It directly ties together disparate parts of an old deck into a modern extender. You could theoretically use Lady of the Lake with this modern card. Don’t actually do it but know you can..

<!-- [if !supportLists]-->·       <!--[endif]-->What is infernoble knight noble knight?

As a refresher/introduction let me explain how this deck works before going into combos. Infernoble Knight Noble knight works by using unique noble knight starters to enable the infernoble knight end board. This deck also still gets to use the classic Noble Knight XYZ monsters for removal and combos.

Angelica into double Charlemange

The basic Infernoble knight combo works like this. Use Infernoble knight Turpin and Oliver to synchro summon into Angelica princess of the noble arms. This can also be done with Ricardetto off of an Isolde Two Tales of the Noble Knights. Angelica is going to let us search Noble Arms Museum. Second, we can attempt to equip an infernoble from graveyard to trigger Angelica’s second effect to tag out into Infernoble knight Vanguard Roland and send whatever infernoble knight we don’t have in grave yet. For this example, I’ll say Magnus.

From here we play an equip or use an Infernoble Knight from grave as an equip to let us summon back turpin from grave. Then we can synchro summon into Infernoble Knight emperor Charles.

After equipping another Infernoble Knight from grave to Charles we then link off into Charlemagne and equip Charles from grave. We then play Noble Arms Museum to search any noble arms card. This can be Camelot for extension or it can be an equip spell to trigger the before-mentioned effects. The point is after that we can use noble arm museum to special summon the equipped Charles. Equip something else to Charles and you can make a second Charlemagne. 

That’s 2 omninegates and a ton of quick effect removal. More so than that this combo plays into our noble knight plays. It can search Camelot, Isolde sets up the old noble arms in graveyard, and we can set it up with our noble knights.

If you sent angelic ring you can re-equip with Charles effect at the end of turn for an extra spell negate. It’s a very powerful card.

Oh yeah if you need any other specific infernoble knight combos. Please check out the Combo sheet by djh_dylan and the Campions of Camelot discord which Is the Infernoble Knight + Noble Knight Discord. The discord is also linked in the description.

<!-- [if !supportLists]-->·       <!--[endif]-->Specific Noble Knight combos

Noble knight medraut + Any infernoble equip spell

For a specific combo example we can use noble knight medraut plus any infernoble equip spell to create an unhand-trappable starter. Medraut can summon any noble knight monster from our deck then pop an equip spell equipped to him. If we special summon infernoble knight Renauld we can immediately add back the equip spell we popped and then make isolde off of out two monsters and go full infernoble knight combo. If the opponent ash blossom or infinite impermence on medraut we just use the infernoble knight equip and go for fire flint lady or a different infernoble depending on the hand. Thus making Isolde anyway.

 

Camelot + Gawayn

A much stronger combo is using Camelot plus noble knight gawayn. Camelot makes it extremely easy to get to Isolde. But if we have gawayn we get to immediately special summon gawayn as well. Of course we can go into isolde here and we should. Isolde lets us then dump 4 equip spells to special summon gigchad. The 4 you dump are destiny, excaliburn, durendal, and almace. Then we can use gigchad’s effect to add back to hand gawayn. Trust me you will have an equip live for this. While we could just make appollosa here theres a much better option.

This combo used to only be do-able with with unexpexted dai as a starter. Now it can be a follow up to a medruat or an infernoble knight combo.

 

Noble knight Artorigus as an extender

We can make artorigus to equip 3 of the spells we just sent to graveyard with Isolde. This is a potential plus 2 as we can trigger out infernoble knight spells for searching. While the other equip spells make our xyz into a towers monster in the process. This is the bread and butter of the deck making artorigus while setting up for infernoble knioght plays as a base. And tying this together is the absurd level of graveyard recursion this deck presents.

These are the basics but there are a few other combos worth considering.

 

The complete board wipe combo

We can use charles’ effect to pop custenian to immediately go into the rank 5 artigous. It works out as a way to remove 3 cards from the opponent’s field and recur value from our equip spells in the game. It’s a ridiculously good recursion especially since the rank 5 artiogious also gets recursion when he leaves the field.

 

<!-- [if !supportLists]-->·       <!--[endif]-->Noble Knight Deck Lists

Here is my deck list for Infernoble Noble knights.

 

This list functions as a Series of two card starters. Medruat plus any equip. Camelot plus gawayn. Gawayn plus any “normal” noble knight. Any two infernoble knight cards. Plus heritage which can become literally anything. It’s absurdly consistent since any two warrior monsters on the field are full combo thanks to Isolde.

Really these card’s work in any combination you have options.

there are a ton of one ofs unfortunately. This deck is very searchable so it works out. Consistency wise some of these one ofs can work as extenders.

I am running barrone plus gearfried to do that extended combo. Gearfried can be sent to graveyard with angelica effect and it can bee added back with Renald or Joyeuse.

This list I’m showing here is going to 43 to fit in 9 hand traps. You can’t realistically play a deck today without some generic help. The side deck covers what the hand traps don’t, and I made sure you’ll have room to put them in thanks to the extended deck size.

I built this as a go first list since realistically there’s no other options for a weaker deck like this.

I am running one caliburn beacuase it wins games in time. It’s not once per turn so you can do some really funny things if need be. Also you don’t have to do this but I think it’s funny. You can side deck in one last chapter of the noble knights going second to get some relatively okay plan b shenanigans going second. It is searchable and usually live playing into most boards.

Alright so that’s about It for noble knights. It’s a very solid deck with tons of great options that really do take an opponent of guard. Especially since they come from such an older and sleep on architype.
